<HEADLINE> Most Pakistanis Welcome Military Takeover: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Eighty percent of Pakistani
people welcomed the taking over of the government by General
Pervez Musharraf in last October, a political survey here showed.
</P>
<P>
According to a report of the state-run Associated Press of
Pakistan (APP) on Sunday, the survey conducted by All Pakistan
Voters Association also showed that 87 percent of people expressed
their love for "true democracy."
</P>
<P>
The survey was conducted in all the four provinces among people
from all walks of life, APP said.
</P>
<P>
In the present circumstances, 52 percent of the population
expressed satisfaction over the steps taken by the present
government, the survey said. People want significant, effective
and positive changes in the situation according to the established
standard of democracy, APP said.
</P>
<P>
The survey also showed that more than half, or 56 percent, of
Pakistanis want to change the country's constitution. The most
common reasons for the change are failure of the previous
governments to enforce the constitution in its entirety, it added.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's armed forced led by General Musharraf dismissed the
former government, which had been mired in political and economic
crunches, on October 12, 1999 and Musharraf assumed the position
of chief executive in the ensuing military government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
