<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Again Demands Inclusion in European Defense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Defense Minister Sabahattin
Cakmakoglu said that Europe should take Turkey into consideration
during the course of its effort to set up a European Security and
Defense Identity (ESDI), the Anatolia News Agency reported on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"Turkey favors a European security and defense mechanism in
which Turkey will be able to fully participate on an equal
footing," the minister said prior to his departure for the United
States to attend a ceremony to be held on the anniversary of the
Second World War Normandy landing.
</P>
<P>
The proposed ESDI envisages the establishment of a decision-
making structure over defense under the European Union, independent
from the U.S.-led North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) and
excluding non-EU members.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, an official EU candidate, has made efforts to join the
European defense mechanism, under the support of the U.S. which was
worried that the ESDI will reduce Washington's role in European
security.
</P>
<P>
Cakmakoglu said that Ankara has been an active contributor,
within the framework of NATO, to European security since the Cold
War and should not be excluded from a European security and defense
architecture.
</P>
<P>
NATO will hold a defense ministers' meeting at Brussels on June
8-9 to assess the latest developments in Kosovo and Bosnia-
Herzegovina. Cakmakoglu said that during the meeting, Turkey will
once again firmly voice its demand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000605.0007 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak, Albright Discuss Israeli-Palestinian Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Israeli-Palestinian peace talks is
the core of the Middle East peace process after Israeli troop
withdrawal from south Lebanon, said U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright here Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the Israeli-Palestinian problem and the difference
between the two sides can only be solved through negotiations,
Albright told reporters after her talks with Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
Albright arrived here earlier Monday afternoon from Moscow for a
two-day visit, aimed at narrowing the difference between Israel and
the Palestinians in reaching a framework agreement on final-status
issues.
</P>
<P>
Albright stressed that in the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks,
proposals and positions of one party can not be 100-percent
satisfactory to the other side, so the peace talks need both sides
to make concessions.
</P>
<P>
Anyway, she said, President Bill Clinton and herself will
continue to make every effort to help the two sides reach a
framework agreement as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Israel and the Palestinians launched their intensive peace talks
in March in the United States to solve the key issues such as the
fate of Jerusalem, Jewish settlements, Palestinian refugees, border
and water. They moved the talks to the region in April.
</P>
<P>
But in May, the two sides opened a secret channel in Stockholm,
capital of Sweden, to speed up the finalization of the framework
agreement. This channel has also been moved to the region by the
end of May.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Public Security Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami, who led the
Israeli delegation to the secret talks, has said that some progress
has been made by the two sides in reaching this framework
agreement.
</P>
<P>
Israeli officials voiced their hope that Albright's current
visit could clear the way for a three-way summit by the end of June
in the United States between Clinton, Barak and Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
It has been hoped that a Camp David-style meeting could solve
the Israeli-Palestinian conflict once and for all. Leaders of the
U.S., Egypt and Israel met in Camp David in 1979 to hammer out a
treaty, the first between an Arab country and the Jewish state, to
realize peace between Egypt and Israel.
</P>
<P>
Barak said that the three-way summit is important for the peace
process, but this summit could only be held when Israel's security
is guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
Barak told his cabinet on Sunday that the summit would see "real
negotiations" on key issues of the final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Israel's next troop redeployment in the West Bank,
Barak promised to complete such a redeployment by the end of June.
But he did not say how many land he will hand over to the
Palestinians in the redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Under the Oslo accords, Israel has to transfer all remaining
West bank territories to the Palestinian in the last redeployment
before reaching a final peace treaty with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
As for the Palestinian refugee problem, he said such issue can
be solved in the final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
On the Israeli-Syrian track, Albright said she will discuss this
issue with Syrian Foreign Minister Faruk Shareh in Cairo on
Wednesday on her way home.
</P>
<P>
The door of the Israeli-Syrian track has not been closed, she
said, but at the movement the major task is to push the Israeli-
Palestinian peace talks forward.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Syrian peace talks stalled again in January after
two rounds in the U.S. starting last December, due to Israel's
refusal to hand over to Syrian the entire Golan Heights it captured
in the 1967 Middle East War.
</P>
<P>
Albright also appreciated Israel's withdrawal from south
Lebanon, saying the pullout was a major step forward in the Middle
East peace process. Israel pulled its troops out on May 24.
</P>
<P>
Albright is scheduled to hold talks with Arafat on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
While Barak and Albright were holding their talks in the Prime
Minister's office, a group of right-wing protestors gathered
outside, asking Barak not to make concessions to the Palestinians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
