<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian Islamic Militant Sentenced to 10-Year Hard Labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's High Security Court on Monday
sentenced an Islamic militant, Mohammed Mustafa Hassan, to 10 years
of forced labor, the country's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Hassan was accused of belonging to an outlawed fundamentalist
group, Jamaa Islamiya, trying to kill police officers, destroy
tourist sites and seek to overthrow the government.
</P>
<P>
He was sentenced to the same punishment in absentia in 1998
after a court tried a group of 22 militants. Under Egyptian law,
persons convicted in absentia must be retried after they are
captured. Hassan was arrested last year.
</P>
<P>
All other members of the group are currently serving labor
sentences except their leader, Mustapha Hamza, who lives in exile.
He is accused of involvement in the attempted assassination of
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak in 1995 when the president visited
Addis Ababa. Hamza was condemned to death in absentia in 1992 and
1994.
</P>
<P>
Jamaa Islamiya began an insurrection in 1992 in an attempt to
topple the secular government and introduce a strict Islamic rule.
It claimed responsibility for killing 58 foreign tourists at
Egypt's Luxor historical site in 1997. Since then the government
has tightened security measures to crack down on Islamic radicals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000605.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek Cypriot Soldier Reportedly Detained by Turkish Troops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- A Greek Cypriot soldier, who was
reported missing Sunday, has been abducted by the Turkish troops in
northern Cyprus, Cyprus News Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Sarah Russell, spokeswoman of UNFICYP (U.N. Peacekeeping Force
in Cyprus) confirmed that the soldier, Giorgos Kasianides, 21, from
Cyprus' southern coastal town of Larnaca, might appear before a "
court" Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We have been in touch with the people in the north and we are
hoping to visit him tomorrow morning," Russell said, adding "we
believe he is due to appear in an illegal court tomorrow morning."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup in Nicosia seeking union with
Athens.
</P>
<P>
Since then Turkey has maintained some 35,000 troops in northern
Cyprus with the claimed aim of protecting the Turkish Cypriot
minority.
</P>
<P>
Russell said that arrangements are being made for an UNFICYP
delegation comprising "our civilian police and an UNFICYP doctor"
to visit Kasianides.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Cyprus' Defense Ministry spokesman Andreas Charides
said the Ministry had received information that Kasianides "had
been abducted by the Turks and taken to the Turkish occupied part
of Nicosia."
</P>
<P>
So far, nobody disclosed why the Turkish troops detained or "
abducted" the Greek Cypriot soldier, and there has been no
information about any comment from the Turkish side on the issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000605.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syria, Qatar to Cement Economic, Trade Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Syria and Qatar have agreed to cut
down tariffs on imported goods on a reciprocal basis by up to 70
percent by 2002 and to tax free a year later, Syrian Arab News
Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed here by Syrian Minister of Economy and
Foreign Trade Mohammed al-Emadi and his Qatari counterpart Yousef
Hussein Kamal at the conclusion of a meeting of the Syrian-Qatari
Joint Commission on Economic and Trade Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed to establish a joint free trade zone
(FTZ) based on granting reciprocal tariff exemption on farm and
animal products and natural wealth, said a communique issued after
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
On agriculture and water cooperation, the two sides also agreed
to
exchange relevant information and study results on plant and animal
diseases control.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, they reached a consensus on the need to avoid double
taxation, and to protect and encourage joint investments. They
pledged to continue the talks on the expert level on the issues
soon, according to the document.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also signed a memorandum of understanding
involving two pacts on cooperation between the Syrian Chambers of
Commerce Union and Qatari Trade and Industry Chamber, and
establishing a businessmen council between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The two pacts provided for exchanging visits between investors
from both countries to get acquainted with the trade opportunities
available in each other's country, launching joint ventures in the
various economic domains, and holding seminars to exchange
information on the incentives and advantages offered for businesses
from both countries.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also signed a memo of understanding on tourism
cooperation and another one on bilateral civil aviation
cooperation, allowing four flights by their carriers per week
between
both states.
</P>
<P>
Yousef Hussein Kamal arrived here on Saturday for a three-day
official visit to Syria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000605.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Entry to WTO To Benefit Spanish Firms: Spanish FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It is now "time to bet for China, which offers opportunities in
infrastructure, energy, agronourishment and tourism sectors", the
foreign minister said at the 5th Hispanic-Chinese Entrepreneurial
Meeting "China and Spain, Always Nearer".
</P>
<P>
This event is being organized, on the eve of official visit of
Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar to China, by Institute of Foreign
Trade (CEOE) and Superior Council of Trade Chambers .
</P>
<P>
Aznar will visit China from June 24 to July 1, accompanied by a
delegation of over 150 Spanish entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
Spanish sales in China in 1999 reached 428.5 million U.S.
dollars, 0.4 percent of total exports of Spain, while imports went
up to 3.5316 billion dollars, 2.7 percent of all Spanish purchases.
</P>
<P>
In China there are 140 Spanish firms, representing only 0.1
percent of all companies with foreign capital established in this
Asian country.
</P>
<P>
State Secretary of Trade and Tourism Juan Costa said China's
forthcoming entry to WTO will bring down tariffs for Spanish
products by half, the average tariff going from 17.5 percent to 8
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
