<DOCNO> XIE20000605.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France to Cut Short Presidential Term to Five Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 5 (Xinhua) -- France will cut short its
presidential term from seven years to five years in a major reform
of the Constitution of the Fifth Republic drafted under General
Charles de Gaulle.
</P>
<P>
French President Jacques Chirac said Monday evening that he
approves a reform which shortens the office of the president by
two years but does not restrict the number of terms to be served
by a French citizen elected president.
</P>
<P>
In a televised interview with TF1 and France 2, Chirac said
that he hopes to push through the constitutional reform through a
referendum by the end of September, after the draft law is adopted
by the National Assembly and the Senate at the end of June before
the parliament deputies leave for summer vacation.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the Socialist government of Prime Minister
Lionel Jospin announced simultaneously that a draft law on
shortening the presidential term will be presented by the
government to the National Assembly on June 14.
</P>
<P>
France will hold its next presidential election in 2002 and
both Chirac, 69, and Jospin, 63, are expected to run for the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
``After I have thought about it and listened to the opinions of
all, I concluded that we can shorten the presidential term from
seven to five years,'' Chirac said.
</P>
<P>
He said that a seven-year presidential term is ``too long
taking into account the modern requests of democracy,'' and that
the French people will have the legitimate right to express their
views on the reform through a referendum.
</P>
<P>
The proposal on shortening presidential office was first made
by former President Valery Giscard d'Estaing on May 9 at the
National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Before that, an opinion poll showed that three in four French
people prefer a five-year presidential term to the present seven-
year term.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, most of the political parties have expressed their
support to shortening the presidential office. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000605.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Government Objects to Key Microsoft Proposals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government rejected
Monday most suggestions from among many offered by Microsoft Corp.
to alter a proposal to break up the company, although it agreed to
a few minor changes.
</P>
<P>
In its last expected court filing before U.S. District Judge
Thomas Penfield Jackson decides how to punish Microsoft, Justice
Department antitrust lawyers rejected the company's suggestion
that a full year be granted to develop details of the breakup plan
for anti-competitive practices, saying that a full year "is
unwarranted."
</P>
<P>
The department has proposed to the judge that "not later than
four months" after a final judgment, the company must submit a
proposed plan for the breakup. Jackson already has found that
Microsoft stifled competition in violation of federal antitrust
law.
</P>
<P>
Government lawyers requested the opportunity to file the legal
brief to present the judge with areas of minor agreements. Most of
these agreements involved definitions, such as using the word "
divestiture" rather than "reorganization."
</P>
<P>
But the Justice Department lawyers, who filed suit along with
19 states, also stated numerous objections to the last proposals
by Microsoft. The company was allowed to comment Wednesday, after
which the judge is expected to rule on his remedy in the case
within a matter of days or weeks.
</P>
<P>
The filings this week do not change the proposal by the
department and 17 of the state plaintiffs that Microsoft be split
into two companies, one built around its Office software and
Internet businesses, and another with its Windows operating-system
software, the source of Microsoft's monopoly power.
</P>
<P>
The brief said many Microsoft suggestions "would create
loopholes and permit Microsoft to continue to engage in anti-
competitive practices like those found by the court or otherwise
to frustrate or undermine the purposes of the final judgment."
</P>
<P>
Among the objections, the department said it disagreed with
Microsoft's proposal to delete a provision involving contracts
with other companies. The government wants to ban the corporation
from entering into contracts that restrict other firms' ability to
develop, distribute and promote non-Microsoft software.
</P>
<P>
"Such agreements were an important part of Microsoft's illegal
campaign against Netscape's browser," the department said.
</P>
<P>
The government also rejected the company's proposal that it not
be required to retain its e-mails. 
</P>
</TEXT>
