<HEADLINE> Mozambican President Calls for Environmental Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican President Joaquim
Chissano Monday called on the people in the country to put
environmental awareness into their daily activities.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a ceremony marking the World Environment Day in the
southern city of Chibuto, which was hit hardest by floods early
this year, Chissano said that the protection of environment has
become the "strategic task" of the government.
</P>
<P>
Noting a periodic recurrence of drought and flooding in
Mozambique in recent years causing great losses to the national
economy, the president stressed that this is a result of the
denudation of natural resources and also a punishment of nature to
human beings.
</P>
<P>
There is an urgent need for the country to kick off a
comprehensive law of environmental protection reinforced with
relevant plans, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, environmental protection is not a task only for the
government, it should become the common sense of the whole society
and be reflected in everybody's daily life and behavior, Chissano
said.
</P>
<P>
People should draw lessons from the devastating flooding in
February and March this year and stop destroying forests to avoid
any further soil erosion, he said.
</P>
<P>
After the ceremony, Chissano joined local people in planting
more than 3, 000 seedlings.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique has frequently suffered from natural disasters
including droughts in the early 1990s and successive floodings in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
It experienced the most serious flooding in the past 50 years
in southern and central parts of the country early this year,
leaving 330,000 people homeless and more than 2 million others
affected.
</P>
<P>
The international community has promised to give the country
425 million U.S. dollars in aid to help those affected by the
floods and to boost the post-disaster rehabilitation work.
</P>
</TEXT>
