<HEADLINE> Lebanon Starts Trial of Collaborators with Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 5 (Xinhua) -- A military tribunal started trial
here Monday of 32 Lebanese, mostly members of the pro-Israeli South
Lebanon Army (SLA), on charges of collaboration with the enemy,
Oriental radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The 32 defendants were charged with "divulging information to
the enemy, collaborating with the enemy and working in Israel,"
said the radio report.
</P>
<P>
Most of the accused were among some 1,700 SLA members who
surrendered to the Lebanese government after Israel's withdrawal
from south Lebanon on May 24. The others were former employees of
the Civil Administration set up by Israel in the occupied border
zone.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that a total of 35 lawyers will form the defense
team for the defendants.
</P>
<P>
The SLA militia, armed and funded by Israel, helped the
occupation troops patrol the so-called security zone carved out by
Israel in 1985 after two invasions.
</P>
<P>
But the 3,000-strong proxy army quickly collapsed as Israel
began pulling out of south Lebanon. Thousands of its members gave
themselves up to Hezbollah guerrillas or Lebanese authorities,
before, during and after the Israeli withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
About 6,000 SLA militiamen and their family members took refuge
in Israel. But some of them have returned to Lebanon as they
preferred facing trial in their home country.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Prime Minster Salim Hoss has urged those Lebanese
staying in Israel to come home to stand for "just trial." 
</P>
</TEXT>
