<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright in Middle East to Mediate Peace Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 5 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright arrived in the Middle East Monday afternoon from Moscow,
hoping to bridge the gap between Israelis and the Palestinians in
reaching a framework agreement on final-status issues.
</P>
<P>
This was Albright's first visit to the region since the Sharm el
Sheikh conference last September, and the visit was arranged during
U.S. President Bill Clinton's talks with Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak in Lisbon, Portugal, last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
During her two-day mission in the region, Albright is scheduled
to hold talks with Barak later in the evening and meet with
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat on Tuesday. She will also travel
to Egypt to hold talks with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak on her
way home.
</P>
<P>
Israeli officials said Monday that they hope Albright could,
during the visit, help narrow the differences between Israel and
the Palestinian side on the key issues in the final-status talks
and clear the way for a three-way summit in the United States by
the end of this month between Clinton, Barak and Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Albright will listen to Barak and Arafat to gauge the degree of
flexibility that they are willing to display, in order to advise
Clinton on the administration's next moves for pushing the Middle
East peace process forward, the officials added.
</P>
<P>
"It seems to me she will take her recommendation to President
Clinton on whether or not to invite the sides to a summit.
Personally I believe that the moment of truth has arrived,"Minister
in the Prime Minister's Office Haim Ramon said.
</P>
<P>
Barak, evoking the Camp David talks that led to the pioneer
Israel-Egypt peace treaty in 1979, told his cabinet on Sunday that
if convened, the summit would see "real negotiations" on key issues
in the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Israeli-Palestinian negotiators launched their intensive final-
status talks in the United States in March and shifted talks to the
region by the end of April. At the same time, they opened a secret
channel in May in Swedish capital Stockholm, aimed at speeding up
talks on reaching the framework agreement.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Public Security Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami, who led the
Israeli delegation at the secret talks, has said the negotiations
have made some progress on all key issues such as the fate of
Jerusalem, Jewish settlement, Palestinian refugees, border and
water.
</P>
<P>
Despite the achievements, differences remain between the two
sides. Israel has insisted on signing this framework agreement
before reaching the final peace treaty by September, while the
Palestinian side proposed to discard the framework accord because
time it short.
</P>
<P>
Israel also rejected the Palestinian demand for transferring to
them, as stipulated by the 1993 Oslo accords, all the occupied
territories before reaching the final peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that Clinton really wants to coax Israel and the
palestinians into another peace deal before leaving office in seven
months. If the final peace treaty can not be signed by September,
then he would try to force the two sides to reach this framework
accord when he is still in office.
</P>
<P>
And that is why he send Albright back to the Middle East this
time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000605.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
