<HEADLINE> Kuwait, Saudi Arabia to Open Talks on Border Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait and Saudi Arabia are due
to start talks in the Saudi capital of Riyadh on Tuesday on the
demarcation of their maritime borders in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Oil Minister Sheikh Saud Nasser Al-Sabah will lead a
high-ranking delegation to Riyadh for the meeting with Saudi
Minister of Petroleum and Mineral Resources Ali Ibrahim al-N'aimi,
Kuwait News Agency reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The talks are aimed at reaching an agreement on the maritime Al-
Dorra gas field located in the continental shelf in a sector in
northern Gulf waters.
</P>
<P>
The demarcation of the continental shelf is subject to rival
claims by Iran, Kuwait and Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
The three Gulf states have been locked in talks for years to
agree on a demarcation scheme, but have failed so far.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, Iran conducted drilling in the disputed area
but stopped the operations in May when the dispute emerged again.
</P>
<P>
Tehran had reportedly expressed readiness to hold meetings with
Kuwait to reach an understanding on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti diplomats in Riyadh said the Kuwaiti-Saudi talks would
be conducted in a manner that protects their joint interests.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, senior Saudi officials have also expressed confidence
that Saudi Arabia and Kuwait would solve the problem soon in a way
that would serve the interests of both states and their "
distinguished relations." 
</P>
