<HEADLINE> Arab Summit Called for Enhancing Arab Cooperation, Coordination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers of eight Arab
countries wound up a two-day meeting on Monday by calling for more
Arab meetings and demanding that Israel withdraw from all Lebanese
lands.
</P>
<P>
The signatories of Damascus Declaration, which consists of Egypt
and Syria and the six members of the Gulf Cooperation Council --
Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, Syria and the United
Arab Emirates -- issued a statement, which urged an Arab summit to
be held "as early as possible to enhance Arab cooperation and
coordination."
</P>
<P>
Only one Arab summit has been held since the 1991 Gulf War,
which was prompted by Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait. The meeting,
held in Cairo in 1996, excluded Iraqi President Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
The ministers agreed on holding an experts meeting to determine
the practical steps to activate relations among the signatories of
the declaration in economic, cultural, scientific and technological
spheres, the statement said, without specifying a date or place.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers also praised the Israeli pullout from
south Lebanon on May 24 as "Lebanese victory resulted from the
solidarity between the government and the people and the Lebanese
resistance.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak met the ministers earlier in
the day. Syrian Foreign Minister Faruk Shareh gave him a message
from President Hafez al-Assad, recalling Syria's position on the
Israeli pullback from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel should not ignore the U.N. Security Council Resolutions
242 and 338 while applying Resolution 425 (on the withdrawal from
Lebanon), Shareh told reporters after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council Resolution 242 of November 1967 called
for an Israeli withdrawal from "territories occupied in the recent
conflict," while 338 of 1973 called for the implementation of 242.
</P>
<P>
Damascus is demanding that Israel withdraw from the whole of the
Golan Heights, which it seized in the 1967 Mideast war and annexed
in December 1981. Israel has said it is ready to withdraw from most
of the strategic plateau, but not back to the line in force when it
captured it.
</P>
<P>
"We shall express our support for Syria and assert our rejection
of any attempt to put pressure on Syria to weaken its position in
the negotiations," Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa said when
the ministerial meeting opened Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Damascus Declaration, signed after the Gulf War in March
1991, was designed to provide political, economic and military
cooperation among its members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
