<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Reiterates Sovereignty Over Disputed Gulf Islands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Iran on Monday reiterated its
sovereignty over three strategic islands in the Persian Gulf, which
are also claimed by the United Arab Emirates (UAE).
</P>
<P>
The three islands, namely Abu Mussa and Greater and Lesser
Tunbs, belong to Iran, Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman Hamid
Reza Asefi was quoted by the Islamic Republic News Agency as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Asefi said that Iran has announced time and again its readiness
to hold direct talks with the UAE within the framework of the 1971
accord so as to iron out differences over the islands.
</P>
<P>
Asefi made the remarks in a response to the recent meeting of
foreign ministers of the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) in Riyadh,
which urged Iran to cooperate with the GCC Tripartite Commission on
the disputed islands to find a peaceful solution.
</P>
<P>
The GCC ministers also voiced willingness to expand ties with
Iran on the principles of good neighborliness, mutual respect, non-
interference in each other's internal affairs and resolving
disputes through peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
Iran took over the three Gulf islands close to the strategic
Hormuz Strait in 1971 after the British colonist forces retreated
from the region. However, Abu Dhabi also claimed sovereignty over
the islands.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the UAE called for international arbitration on
the dispute, but Iran insisted on direct bilateral talks to remove
the "misunderstanding". 
</P>
</TEXT>
