<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan: World Future Depends on Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Women not only belong to
this planet, but the future of this planet depends on women, U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan stressed here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Opening the United Nations General Assembly special session on
women, held here at the Headquarters of the United Nations in New
York from June 5 to 9, Annan said since the Fourth World
Conference on Women in 1995, much progress has been achieved in
promoting the Equality between men and women.
</P>
<P>
"Violence against women is now illegal almost everywhere. There
has been worldwide mobilization against harmful traditional
practices such as so-called'honor killings'. In many countries,
new health strategies have saved thousands of women's lives,"
Annan said.
</P>
<P>
"And a record number of women have become leaders and decision-
makers. Above all, more countries have understood that women's
equality is a prerequisite for development," Annan continued.
</P>
<P>
However, Annan noted, much remains to be done. "In economic
terms, the gender divide is still widening. Women earn less, are
more often unemployed and generally are poor than men."
</P>
<P>
"Violence against women is still increasing -- both in the home
and in new types of armed conflict which target civilian
population, with women and children as the first causalities,"
Annan said.
</P>
<P>
Annan listed the spread of AIDS and trafficking of women and
children as the new challenges which should be addressed with
immediate action from all Member States.
</P>
<P>
"I have asked Member States, when they gather for the
Millennium Summit in September, to adopt specific goals for
halting and reversing the spread of HIV/AIDS," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
To address all the old and new challenges, women must be
educated and enabled to play part in the global economy, Annan
noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
