<HEADLINE> Suspect Admits Sabotaging Railway in Train Derailment in France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The suspect arrested by French police
for allegedly sabotaging a railway and causing a train derailment
Sunday morning in southern France has admitted his act, said
French Interior Minister Jean-Pierre Chevenement on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Two passengers were killed and 12 injured in the derailment of
an international passenger train from Vintimille, Italy, to Calais,
northern France.
</P>
<P>
The suspect, Moussa Hammoudi, is a 32-year-old Algerian man who
had psychiatric problems because of brain damages caused by a car
accident, said Chevenement.
</P>
<P>
The interior minister also ruled out the possibility of an
involvement by the Algerian terrorist group GIA and said the
accident was created by ``an act of malice'' by Hammoudi alone.
</P>
<P>
Hammoudi himself also said that he acted alone and no one else
helped him, said police.
</P>
<P>
He admitted placing some rails on the railway track in a
southern French town called Chasse-sur-Rhone in order to derail
the train.
</P>
</TEXT>
