<DOCNO> XIE20000605.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Sees Men Part of Solution to AIDS Spread </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In many places HIV infection in young women has been found to
be 3-5 times higher than among boys, said Dr. Peter Piot,
Executive Director of the Joint U.N. Program on HIV/AIDS (UNAIDS).
He called on men to change their behavior to help get the epidemic
slow down.
</P>
<P>
Tracing biological and social factors which make women and
girls more vulnerable to AIDS than men, Piot said violence or the
threat of violence against women increases their vulnerability to
HIV, the virus causing AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Besides, women's dependence on men makes them less able to
protect themselves, he told the U.N. Special Session on the follow-
up to the Fourth International Conference on Women.
</P>
<P>
U.N. figures show that 33.6 million people were living with HIV
or AIDS, and 16.3 million had already died from the disease by the
end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
There were 5.6 million new infections worldwide. of which 3.8
million were in sub-Saharan Africa, and 1.3 million in South and
Southeast Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000605.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Urged to Strengthen Conflict Resolution Mechanisms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Robert Okello, director of the
Economic Commission for Africa (ECA) and the Southern African
Sub-regional Development Center, has urged Africa to strengthen
mechanisms for conflict prevention and resolution so as to promote
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Opening the ECA sub-regional training workshop on Developing
Civil Society Organizations (CSO) Capacity for Conflict Prevention
and Resolution here on Monday, Okello said the African continent
is currently plagued by many internal conflicts.
</P>
<P>
The "African renaissance" witnessed in the mid-1990's could
have produced more tangible progress if African countries had been
able to prevent conflicts, he said, noting that in Africa, the
best performing countries in the economic and social sphere are
those that have avoided conflicts.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, the ECA, as an organ of Africa and
the United Nations, advocates that greater attention be paid to
measures for preventing or containing crises before they erupt
into violent confrontation.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that one third of the population of Africa
suffers from direct consequences of on-going conflicts.
</P>
<P>
There is an urgent need to prevent conflicts and disputes from
escalating into armed hostilities, and this calls for the
strengthening of conflict resolution mechanisms for negotiation,
mediation, conciliation and arbitration at the governmental,
political and diplomatic levels, he said.
</P>
<P>
"In the final analysis, we should bear in mind that peace and
development are two sides of the same coin, which means that
Africa's development will not occur in the unstable and insecure
environment created by conflicts," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
"Durable peace can only be achieved with development," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The three-day workshop has gathered representatives from
Zambia, Mozambique, Zimbabwe and Lesotho. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
