<DOCNO> XIE20000605.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambican Coastal, Marine Project Boosted by World Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has approved, through
its soft loans affiliate, the International Development
Association, a 5.6 million U. S. dollar credit for Mozambique to
assist its government in achieving sustainable economic
development of coastal zone resources.
</P>
<P>
According to a World Bank press release received here on
Monday, the credit supplements an earlier 4.1 million U.S. dollar
grant from the bank's Global Environmental Facility.
</P>
<P>
"The funds will support the coastal and marine biodiversity
management project, which is a key element of Mozambique's
National Coastal Zone Management Program -- in particular its
strategy for coastal and marine biodiversity protection and
sustainable use of natural resources," the news release said.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that the project, to be tested in the northern
provinces of Nampula and Cabo Delgado, will pilot and refine an
approach through strategic development planning that balances
ecological, social and physical values with the various
development interests in the coastal area.
</P>
<P>
The project will seek to introduce strategic spatial planning
that fully integrates conservation with regional development. It
is intended to establish and strengthen protection of key
terrestrial and marine conservation areas and initiate
conservation-oriented activities for communities.
</P>
<P>
The project also aims to establish best practices for
environmentally and biodiversity-friendly economic development and
strengthen institutional arrangements for devolving coastal and
marine resource planning to provincial and local levels.
</P>
<P>
Apart from Madagascar, Mozambique is the only country in the
East African Marine Region with major brackish coastal barrier
lagoons and supports the most extensive mangrove forests and sea
grass beds, as well as the best coral assemblages, along the East
African mainland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
