<HEADLINE> Tanzania Listed Among Top African Nations to Attract More Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has told
Tanzania it is among the top three poor African countries that may
attract more funding due to its impressive economic recovery
performance and good governance.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters before launching a new report on Africa's
outlook here on Monday, the bank's chief economist in Africa Alen
Gelb said Tanzania should be one of the top three African
countries that are bound to attract more funding due to its good
economic record.
</P>
<P>
However, he did not identify the other two countries.
</P>
<P>
Gelb explained that countries likely to qualify for more
funding are those with good governance, good economic performance
records and a decreasing level of poverty in that country.
</P>
<P>
He said the poverty alleviation initiative implemented in
Tanzania under the Highly Indebted Poor Countries (HIPC) program
is the most impressive in the fight against poverty.
</P>
<P>
On the new report titled "Can Africa Claim the 21st Century",
Gelb said it is not a panacea to resolve African continent
problems, but simply a review of major setbacks hampering
development in the region.
</P>
<P>
He listed the major hindrances to African economic development
as civil wars, HIV/AIDS, poor levels of infrastructure and
education.
</P>
<P>
The report suggested fundamental policy changes in Africa and
the needs for its economy to grow by 5 percent a year in order to
keep the poverty from growing.
</P>
<P>
It has been jointly prepared by the United Nations Economic
Commission for Africa, the Global Coalition for Africa, the World
Bank, the African Development Bank and the African Economic
Research Consortium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
