<HEADLINE> Local Media Must Remain in Local Hands: S'pore Govt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore government
reiterated in a press release Monday that the country's media must
remain in local hands and there should be no foreign influence.
</P>
<P>
"It is for this reason that we have rules limiting any
individual shareholding to no more than three percent and
requiring board members of media companies to be mainly
Singaporeans," the press release said.
</P>
<P>
This is because local media have a unique nation-building role
in Singapore's multiracial and multireligious society and they
need to have a deep sense of responsibility and commitment to
Singapore, it said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in his speech at the opening of the Digital TV
Seminar Monday, Minister for Information and the Arts Lee Yock
Suan announced that the Singapore government will retain the
present local media industry structure, with the Singapore Press
Holdings (SPH) as the core newspaper group and the Mediacorp as
the core broadcaster.
</P>
<P>
"Various options were considered, and the government decided
that under current circumstances, allowing SPH and Mediacorp to
compete with each other whilst encouraging them to move
aggressively into the Internet was the best option," he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister also announced that the government is prepared to
issue SPH with broadcasting licenses to run up to two free-to-air
TV channels and up to two radio channels and to issue Mediacorp a
newspaper license in order to give scope for more direct
competition between SPH and Mediacorp and enrich their position as
content providers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
