<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Digital Distribution Planned for Titan A.E. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 5 (Xinhua) -- A Hollywood movie will be
digitally distributed across the country and then projected to a
cinema audience, going from the studio in Hollywood to a theater
in Atlanta without ever touching film.
</P>
<P>
The announcement, made by 20th Century Fox and Cisco Systems,
is to demonstrate the potential of digital distribution, which
many believe will one day replace film, the New York Times
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Using Cisco's new technology, Fox's new animated feature, "
Titan A.E." will be hurled from West Communication's CyberCenter
in Burbank to the Woodruff Arts Center in Atlanta, where it will
be projected.
</P>
<P>
Digital projectors have been used occasionally in the last year
to exhibit a few films in a handful of theaters around the country,
and video images have been played across the Internet.
</P>
<P>
However, this will be the first time the two processes have
been combined in a demonstration of the kind of digital
distribution network.
</P>
<P>
It is still a question how long it might be before such digital
distribution is common. Two major issues have been slowing the
transition.
</P>
<P>
The first is the price. Cinema owners are reluctant to pay an
estimated 100,000 U.S. dollars per projector. The second issue is
the fear among many in Hollywood that once their films are loosed
upon the Internet, they will be subject to the same kinds of
piracy that have plagued the music industry in recent months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
