<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Debt Estimated to Drop in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Canada's net debt is predicted to
drop to 568.8 billion Canadian dollars in 2000 (about 385.6
billion U.S. dollars), the country's Globe and Mail newspaper said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Canadian Finance Minister Paul Martin as
saying that the federal government may post a surplus of at least
8 billion Canadian dollars (about 5.4 billion U.S. dollars) to
boost health and education spending while paying down national
debt.
</P>
<P>
Martin attributed the sound prediction to a bigger-than-
expected 1999-2000 surplus which means that the federal government
will have to allocate less of its spending to debt payments in
future years.
</P>
<P>
Canada's booming economy should also provide longer-term
support to the Canadian dollar, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
