<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Chinese Keen on Environmental Reports (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 5 (Xinhua) -- A number of Chinese provinces and
cities today published local environmental reports to mark the
World Environment Day, designated as the day to expose global
concerns about environmental pollution and honor the achievements
in environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen, which came first in the comprehensive assessment of
environment situation among 46 major cities in China last year,
today released a comprehensive environmental situation bulletin.
</P>
<P>
The city pooled 2.6 billion yuan for its environmental
protection programs in 1999, which accounted for 1.85 percent of
its GDP for the year, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen has set strict rules against pollution, which were put
into effect to deal with 831 cases of pollution violations last
year, the report says.
</P>
<P>
The city's environmental department has been given the power to
veto projects that pose environment threats. The right was
exercised to reject 892 of the total 9,564 new projects passed
last year in the coastal special economic zone.
</P>
<P>
The environmental report published by the Tibet Autonomous
Region today focuses on water quality. It says that the abundant
water reserve in the region has been well preserved. The region
boasts 448.2 billion cu m of surface water and 110.7 billion cu m
of ground water.
</P>
<P>
However, the report warns that urbanization has produced an
increase of residential sewage discharge, which added up to 49.8
million tons last year. It also points out that industrial sewage
discharge lessened due to improved disposal technology.
</P>
<P>
East China's Jiangxi Province today released its environmental
situation bulletin for the year 1999, in which it announces its
better air quality but worsening the acid rain problem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
