<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia Reviews Oil Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIYADH, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia is currently reviewing
the situation in world oil market with regard to prices, supply and
demand, crude reserves and derivatives, said Minister of Petroleum
and Mineral Resources Ali Ibrahim al-N'aimi.
</P>
<P>
The review aimed to strike a balance between supply and demand
in world oil market, maintain the stability of prices to the
benefits of both producers and consumers, ensure a reasonable
revenue for oil producers and the oil industry in general, and
reduce possible  impacts to be inflicted by oil on world economy,
Saudi Press Agency quoted the minister as saying Monday.
</P>
<P>
The kingdom, in cooperation with other producers, will take the
necessary steps to bring down the rising oil prices to a reasonable
level, stressed the minister of the world's largest oil producer.
</P>
<P>
Member states of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries (OPEC), excluding Iraq, agreed in March to increase their
daily oil output by 1.7 million barrels as of April 1 to stabilize
the oil prices that had risen to a nine-year high of more than 30
U.S. dollars a barrel.
</P>
<P>
OPEC, which dominates 42 percent of the world oil market, groups
Algeria, Indonesia, Iran, Iraq, Kuwait, Libya, Nigeria, Qatar,
Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates and Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
The price of the North Sea Brent crude surged on Friday above
the 29-U.S.-dollar per barrel ceiling in London while the price of
the light reference in New York spiralled over 30 dollars per
barrel.
</P>
<P>
Many OPEC members announced recently that they might
automatically boost their production in accordance with the
mechanism adopted in their March meeting.
</P>
<P>
OPEC oil ministers will hold an extraordinary meeting on June
21 in Vienna to review the effects of the oil production hike.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
