<HEADLINE> Victims Families to Probe Philippine Air Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Families of the victims who were
killed on April l9 when Air Philippines flight 54l crashed in the
southern Philippines have agreed to pursue the probe into the air
disaster, Philippine News Agency (PNA) said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The PNA said relatives representing some 32 families met last
Friday in Davao city to forge the agreement and organized a core
group that will take up the cudgels for all the victims and their
families.
</P>
<P>
They will carry out their common cause "no matter who gets hurt
" in the interest of "truth and justice," the victims relatives
were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Starting off from Manila in the early morning on April 19, the
plane crashed two hours later in Samal Island five minutes away
from the Davao International Airport. All of the 124 passengers
and 7 crew members on board were confirmed dead.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Philippine air authority said the data box and
voice recorder set in the plane have been sent to the United
States for further analysis. But no feedback has been reported
ever since.
</P>
<P>
Calling themselves the "Flight 541 Assistance Group," the
victims' relatives said they have elected an eight-man executive
committee tasked to plan the course of actions and legal
strategies until "justice is done." 
</P>
