<HEADLINE> Telekom Malaysia to Rationalize Cellular Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's largest
telecommunication company Telekom Malaysia Bhd announced Monday
that it will rationalize its cellular phone network operations.
</P>
<P>
The company has allocated 800 million ringgit (210.526 million
U.S. dollars) for the rationalization plan under which Telekom
Malaysia would increase the coverage of one desired network, its
newly appointed Chief Executive Officer Mohd Khir Abdul Rahman
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Mohd Khir, however, did not say whether there would be a merger
between the existing two cellular networks, namely, the 018
Mobikom network and the 013 TM Touch network, or whether one would
be phased out.
</P>
<P>
TM Touch is currently more popular with its subscribers
reaching 233,000 people in 1999, while Mobikom has 142,000
subscribers.
</P>
<P>
Mohd Khir said for Telekom now, the priority is to put in more
effort to clean the cellular network by way of improving its
operations and services.
</P>
<P>
He expected the cellular phone subscriber base to increase by
between 15 and 20 percent within the next two to three years from
its current level.
</P>
<P>
Telekom has been very strong in fixed line telephony with a 98
percent market share, with a subscriber base of about 4.3 million
people at the end of 1999 in the fixed line area. 
</P>
