<HEADLINE> S. Leone Urges Deployment of West African Peacekeeping Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leone has demanded immediate
deployment of the 3,000-strong West African Peacekeeping Forces
(ECOMOG) pledged by the regional leaders last week, local press
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Sierra Leone's High Commissioner (ambassador) to Nigeria Joe
Blell said on Sunday in the Nigerian capital Abuja that the
troops' timely deployment would forestall the continued violation
of the Lome peace agreement by the Revolutionary United Front
(RUF) rebels.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the Economic Community of West African States
(ECOWAS) agreed to provide the additional troops to reinforce the
U.N. peacekeeping forces which have been deployed in Sierra Leone
since April to oversee the disarmament and demobilization of about
45,000 rebels under the Lome peace accord signed last July.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made after the RUF rebels who refused to hand
over weapons took about 500 U.N. peacekeepers hostage in early
May, pushing the war-torn west African country back on the brink
of all-out civil war.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria, Ghana and Mali have already sent a total of six
battalions to the U.N. mission in that country.
</P>
<P>
The envoy denied that the arrested RUF leader Foday Sankoh
would be flown to another country for security reason.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated the position of his government that the rebel
leader would be tried "at some point in time" and in line with the
laws of that country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
