<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Government Warns Companies Against Political Closures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government has issued
a strong warning Monday of dire consequences to companies
allegedly closing down deliberately to cause economic chaos in
the run-up to the June 24 and 25 parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Minister of the Industry and Commerce Ministry Obert
Mpofu said his ministry was compiling names of companies where
mostly white managers had cut down whole or sections of
production to create commodity shortages that could result in
panic consumerism.
</P>
<P>
Some of the managers were reportedly sending workers on forced
unpaid leave and telling them that if they vote for the
opposition, they would get their jobs back. But if they returned
the ruling Zimbabwe African National Union-Patriotic Front
(Zanu-pf) to power they would suffer job losses.
</P>
<P>
"We have received a lot of reports," said Mpofu without
elaborating.  " We are taking stock and compiling the names.
When we come back into power we will not hesitate to help workers
to buy those companies."
</P>
<P>
Mpofu's warning was coming at a time when many workers across
the entire economy had been reporting incidents that bosses sent
them on indefinite leave or dismissed them completely.
</P>
<P>
They were telling the workers that they were being forced to
close businesses because of the plunder of the economy by
Zanu-pf.
</P>
<P>
White bosses in particular were said to be closing temporarily
to go on "holiday" abroad as they anticipated violence and
property destruction during the elections.
</P>
<P>
Police and travel agencies reported that on a daily basis more
than 100 white families apply to leave the country just before
the elections.
</P>
<P>
Mpofu blamed opposition leaders who de-campaigned the local
economy to the point of calling for sanctions against Zimbabwe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
