<HEADLINE> Most Thais for Bangkok Olympics 2008 Bid, Says Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Most Thai people have expressed
their support for Bangkok to host Olympic Games 2008, as results
of a recent poll were made known by a government official here on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The international Olympic Committee will announce on August 30
the countries which win the first-round of the selection process.
</P>
<P>
Lertratana Ratanavanich, Chairman of a government sub-committee
in charge of seeking Thai people's support for Bangkok's bid, said
that a recent poll found that most respondents, or 79.28 percent,
backed Bangkok to host the 29th Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
The poll, conducted by Rajabhat (Suan Dusit) Institute between
May 22 and 26, randomly interviewed 2,000 Thai people, 45 percent
of which male and 55%female, aged between 15 and over 50, in
Bangkok and its peripheral areas, as well as in four other regions
of the country, including the North, East, Northeast and South, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Most respondents, or 85.5 percent, said that if Bangkok was
selected to be the Olympic host, it would help promote Thailand's
tourism, arts and culture in the international community.
</P>
<P>
They also said the event would encourage Thai youths to love
sports, boost the country's prestige as the host of the world's
sport event, strengthen ties and cooperation with other countries,
bring in foreign exchanges and generate activities in the Thai
economy.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chetha Thanajaro, Chairman of the Olympic Committee
of Thailand, told a news conference on Monday morning that support
from people in countries bidding to host the 2008 Olympic Games
was a key factor helping the countries to win the bid.
</P>
<P>
He then urged the Thai people to solidly support Bangkok's
contest with other nine cities in all region of the world, to host
the 29th Olympic Games and to actively back campaigns to be
launched by authorities concerned.
</P>
<P>
The campaign center was located at the World Trade Centre here,
with an overall earmarked budget of about 60 billion baht (1.6
billion U.S. dollars), he noted.
</P>
<P>
The Bangkok Metropolitan Administration (BMA) announced
recently that it would open a web site, bangkokgames.com, to
promote Bangkok as the host of the world sport's event, as well as
to publicize Thai values and cultures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
