<HEADLINE> Coach Ma Doubtful of Olympic Gold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINZHOU, Northeast China, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Legendary Chinese
coach Ma Junren said here on Monday that he was not confident of
his runners winning any gold medal at the Sydney Olympic Games in
September.
</P>
<P>
Ma, who stunned the world by leading his long-distance women
runners to three gold medals in the Stuttgart world championships
in 1993, has not appeared in international arena for about two
years.
</P>
<P>
"I know the whole country expect us to win a gold medal at
Olympics, but this is very difficult," said Ma, who is here to
compete for the national Olympic athletics trials set for June 7-8.
</P>
<P>
"The reason is very clear," Ma said. "Firstly, our runners were
out of practice for about two years from 1998 to 1999. We just
resumed systematic training last summer. Secondly, quite a few
talented runners in the west have emerged during this period.
They are more experienced and will pose serious threat to us in
the Olympics."
</P>
<P>
Ma added: "Almost all my runners are plagued with injuries.
Jiang Bo had to pull out of the Olympic trials because of a knee
injury."
</P>
<P>
Jiang set a new world record in women's 5,000 meters event by
clocking 14 minutes 28.09 seconds in the China's Eighth National
Games in 1997 in Shanghai. 
</P>
</TEXT>
