<HEADLINE> Simulated Marine Rescue Exercise Held </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, June 5 (Xinhua) -- China held an inter-regional
marine emergency exercise near the Shenzhen Special Economic Zone
today.
</P>
<P>
The five-hour exercise, organized by the Ministry of
Communications and China Marine Salvage Center, is the largest
marine rescue ever held in the country and the first exercise
jointly organized by Guangdong, Hong Kong and Macao after Macao
returned to the motherland last year.
</P>
<P>
In a simulated disaster at sea, a 3,000-dwt oil tanker was sent
crashing into a cargo ship and instantly caught on fire. The ship'
s crew sent a rescue signal and jumped the ship. Over 5,000 tons
of oil on board the ship was about to spill into the sea, which
will cause serious pollution in the waters off Shenzhen, Hong Kong
and Macao.
</P>
<P>
More than 40 vessels and two helicopters from the three regions
rushed to the scene for rescue.
</P>
<P>
The exercise tested the ability of marine departments of the
three regions to react quickly under pressure, organize their
members, coordinate in joint rescue operations, and remove
pollutants using modern equipment, said the organizers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
