<DOCNO> XIE20000605.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Curbs Worsening of Environment (More Added) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 5 (Xinhua) -- China has prevented its natural
environment from getting any worse, and the environmental
situation in some parts of the country has improved, according to
an official report released here today.
</P>
<P>
However, the China Environmental Situation Bulletin 1999 warned
that the overall environmental situation in China remains serious,
as the total volume of pollutants discharged across the country
continues to be too high.
</P>
<P>
The bulletin, released here today by the State Environmental
Protection Administration (SEPA), gives facts and figures on the
current state of China's water, ocean, air, noise, solid
industrial waste, radiation, land resources, biodiversity, climate
change and natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
The report says that in 1999 the Chinese government increased
spending on the urban infrastructure construction and
environmental protection and worked to prevent pollution and
protect the ecology.
</P>
<P>
"The total pollutant discharge amount was controlled
effectively," says the official report.
</P>
<P>
China increased its national debts by 60 billion yuan (7.2
billion U.S. dollars) last year and 23.1 percent of the amount was
put into environmental projects, including construction of natural
gas and urban sewage treatment facilities, and control of
pollution of major rivers and lakes.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the discharge amount of sulfur dioxide,
and smoke and dust in China reduced 10 and 20 percent respectively
over 1998.
</P>
<P>
Unleaded gasoline accounted for over 70 percent of the total
gasoline consumption in the country. But the total discharge
amount of the industrial and urban sewage in the whole country was
40.1 billion tons, 600 million tons more than in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The report points out that most rivers in the country are
contaminated. The pollution in the Liao River and the Hai River is
serious, and the water quality in the Huai River is bad. The water
quality in the Yellow River is worrisome. Only the Songhua River,
Pearl River and Yangtze River were reported to be in good
condition. The spread of oxygen-eating algae in the Tai, Dian and
Chao lakes is serious.
</P>
<P>
Among the 47 major cities, only 16 passed the national standard
for air quality and 20 passed the ground water quality standard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000605.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Will Not Meet Undue Greenhouse Gas Reduction Standards: Official (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 5 (Xinhua) -- China said today it will not
attempt to meet the standards of greenhouse gas reduction that are
required of developed countries, but reaffirmed that it will
continue to reduce the gas emission within its limited capability.
</P>
<P>
Xie Zhenhua, director of the State Environmental Protection
Administration (SEPA), made the remark here today in a response to
a question at a press conference hosted by the State Information
Office of the State Council.
</P>
<P>
Some developed countries have been asking developing countries
like China to make the same substantial cut in greenhouse gas
emission as required of developed countries by international
conventions or protocols.
</P>
<P>
Xie also called on the developed countries to honor their
commitments and international obligations, such as those made at
the world's first Earth Summit in Brazil in the early 1990s and
greenhouse gas emission targets for developed countries as listed
in the Kyoto Protocol, in a bid to help developing countries in
environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
He said that China and Britain agree that developed countries
should fulfill their obligations to global greenhouse gas
reduction and global environmental cooperation between the rich
and the poor countries.
</P>
<P>
The SEPA director said China has made great efforts to cut the
gas emission by improving its energy consumption mix and
encouraging the use of renewable and clean energy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000605.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Will Not Meet Undue Greenhouse Gas Reduction Standards: Official (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China has shut down 33,000 coal mines in the past few years,
reducing the country's annual coal output by 280 million tons, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Efforts have been stepped up to develop water power resources
in southwest China, and the Three Gorges project on the Yangtze
River is progressing smoothly, Xie said.
</P>
<P>
The project's power station has a designed capacity to produce
as much power as the burning of 50 million tons of coal each year.
</P>
<P>
Progress has been made in the use of wind power resources in
the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region in north China and the
Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region in the northwest, as well as in
the exploitation of solar energy in western China. Research is
underway to use tidal waves along the country's eastern coast to
produce power.
</P>
<P>
China is also working on at least two new nuclear power
stations aimed to increase its nuclear energy output and to
optimize its energy mix, which now is heavily dependent on coal
consumption, he added.
</P>
<P>
"In rural China, efforts have been made to encourage the use of
organic resources to produce environment-friendly methane for
cooking and lighting," Xie said.
</P>
<P>
The ongoing large-scale program to return farmland to grassland,
lakes, and forests, and the ambitious plan to double China's land
covered by forest in the coming three or four decades will also
help reduce the greenhouse gas emission, Xie said.  
</P>
