<HEADLINE> Nanometric Technology to Become Hot Scientific Field in 21st Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Nanometric technology will become
one of the most important scientific fields in the 21st century,
along with information and biology technology, a foreign
academician with the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS) said today.
</P>
<P>
This new technology, which is closely related to physics,
chemistry, material science and biological engineering, has huge
potential in application, and Western developed countries
including the United States are investing big money to develop it,
said Prof. Chang-Lin Tien, a Chinese-American scientist.
</P>
<P>
One nanometer is only 1/1,000,000,000 of a meter. However, the
nanometric technology will lead to important developments in
clinical medicine, computer hardware, environmental protection and
other fields.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Tien said that the nanometric research in China is still
in a preliminary stage, but Chinese scientists have already made
some achievements in the field.
</P>
<P>
Researchers with the Physics Institute under the CAS have
succeed in developing the longest and thinnest carbon nanotubes
during the past two years. A medical high-tech company in the
eastern China city of Nanjing has developed a super anti-bacteria
cotton fabric using the nanometric techniques.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Tien, who was elected to be in the first group of CAS'
foreign academicians in 1994, has been actively involved in
academic activities in China and has made contributions in
promoting the country's international exchanges in science and
technology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000605.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five Israelis Sentenced in Maccabiah Disaster Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Five Israelis were sentenced
Monday to a 21-month imprisonment or community services for their
negligence which led to a bridge collapse during the Maccabiah
Games in Israel three years ago.
</P>
<P>
The tragedy took place on the occasion of the opening ceremony
of the 15th Maccabiah Games, or the Jewish Olympics, on July 14,
1997, in which four Australian Jewish athletes were killed and
nearly seventy injured. 
</P>
<P>
When the Australians were crossing a temporary footbridge over
the Yarkon River into the Ramat Gan stadium near Tel Aviv, the
bridge collapsed and about 100 people were plunged into the
polluted river.
</P>
<P>
Israel's Tel Aviv Magistrate's court Monday sentenced Micha Bar-
Ilan, the engineer who designed the bridge, to one year and nine
months in prison, with a 21-month suspended sentence.
</P>
<P>
It was established during the trial that Bar-Ilan did not take
actions when learning that hundreds of persons would be on the
bridge even though its design could only accommodate 100 persons.
</P>
<P>
Two sub-contractors Yehoshua Ben Ezra and Baruch Kegula were
sentenced to 15 months and a two-year suspended sentence, according
to the court's verdict.
</P>
<P>
Adam Mishori, the manager of the Irgunit company which supplied
materials for the bridge, was sentenced to nine months in prison
with a 15-month suspended sentence as well.
</P>
<P>
Yoram Eyal, head of the Games' organizing committee, was ordered
to accomplish six-month community services.
</P>
<P>
All the defendants, except Eyal, had appealed to the Tel Aviv
District Court. Their lawyers had asked the court to put off their
client's sentence until the appeal procedure finished.
</P>
<P>
The five, who played key organizational roles in the games, were
convicted in April of causing death and injuries by negligence. All
had faced a maximum prison term of four years.
</P>
<P>
The Magistrate's Court judges stated Monday that the sentences
were intended to serve as a deterrent to prevent such negligence
and lack of responsibility in the future.
</P>
<P>
However, Colin Elterman, whose daughter Sasha was among the
victims and is still undergoing medical treatments for her injuries
from that day, expressed his angry and disappointment over the
verdict.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to Israel Radio on the telephone from Australia,
Elterman said: "It's an absolute disgrace. The minimum sentence in
Australia for a crime like this...would have been four years in
jail."
</P>
<P>
He also called on Israelis to boycott the next Maccabiah Games
and commercial sponsors supporting the games.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the court rejected the prosecutor's claims that the
five defendants should compensate the victims as the matter is
being addressed in a separate civil suit, which already opened at
the Haifa District Court on May 23.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-three victims of the Maccabiah bridge disaster are seeking
compensation for their injuries, which could result in more than
one million U.S. dollars in compensation for the plaintiffs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
