<DOCNO> XIE20000605.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Earthquake Death Toll Reaches 58 in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- A strong earthquake measuring 7.9
on the Richter Scale and scores of aftershocks rocked Bengkulu in
the Indonesian island of Sumatra, killing at least 58 people and
leaving more than 200 injured, according to latest reports
reaching here Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The Antara News Agency quoted police in Bengkulu as saying that
the death toll is likely to rise considering the magnitude of the
quake.
</P>
<P>
"So far we have received a report of 58 people dead and more
than 200 people injured from the whole of the province. But the
death toll is likely to be higher because we have not been able to
contact the worst-hit area, which is the South Bengkulu district,"
Sergeant Edy Somes was quoted by the reports as saying.
</P>
<P>
Antara reported that most of the wounded people were laid on
the corridors of the hospitals in Bengkulu because they do not
have enough rooms for all the victims.
</P>
<P>
Wounded people screamed as doctors performed operations on them
because there was not enough anesthesia. Hospitals reported they
were running out of blood and medicine as they tried to cope with
the flood of injured.
</P>
<P>
"Relief aid for the earthquake victims in Bengkulu will be sent
immediately and the technical aspects are currently being
discussed by the ministry of health and welfare," President
Abdurrahman Wahid told a press conference here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Rescue efforts were being hampered by the lack of electricity,
which had been knocked out by the tremor. Water supply had also
been cut and public transport disrupted. Bengkulu airport stopped
operations and the navigational system and power generators there
were said to have been damaged.
</P>
<P>
Bengkulu Governor Hasan Zein told state television that most
houses on Enggano island, which lies close to the earthquake's
epicenter and is home to 1,500 people, had been flattened.
</P>
<P>
Telephone lines to Enggano and other remote parts of the
province have been severed.
</P>
<P>
Head of the local Meteorological and Geophysics Office Armin
Paimin said the epicenter of the quake was located 112 kilometers
from Bengkulu off the west coast of Sumatra, and 200 aftershocks
were recorded following the earthquake.
</P>
<P>
The earthquake also sparked panic in the Sumatran cities of
Jambi, Padang, Palembang and Lampung, although there was no report
of casualties there.
</P>
<P>
The quake was also felt as far away as in Jakarta, 536
kilometers southeast of the epicenter.
</P>
<P>
Armin said Bengkulu, which sits on an earthquake zone, is
shaken by light tremors almost every day.
</P>
<P>
A strong earthquake measuring 6 on the Richter Scale shook
Bengkulu on December 15, 1978, leaving one dead.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia is prone to earthquakes as it is situated at the
Pacific "Ring of Fire," a string of volcanoes and earthquake zones
that stretch from Mexico to New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
The worst earthquake to hit Indonesia in the last decade
occurred in December 1992, when a magnitude 7 earthquake and a
tsunami killed 2,200 persons on Flores island in eastern part of
the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
