<HEADLINE> Kumaratunga Rules Out Unconditional Talks With Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan President Chandrika
Kumaratunga has ruled out the possibility of holding "
unconditional" talks with the Tamil Tiger rebels who seem to be on
the defensive after a fierce offensive over the past two months in
the northern Jaffna peninsula.
</P>
<P>
In a BBC interview which went on air on Monday, Kumaratunga
said, "previously, there were no conditions except for a limited
time frame."
</P>
<P>
She said, "for six years we have tried to talk to them and for
six years they have lied (that) they are going to talk, and up to
date, they have refused. Now there is no question of talking
unless certain conditions are fulfilled."
</P>
<P>
However, the president did not spell out what the conditions
for the talks would be. She only said they would have to be
considered when the time came.
</P>
<P>
Kumaratunga said the government had direct contacts with the
separatist Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) through the
Norwegian government which is acting as a facilitator to bring
both parties to the peace negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
She also indicated that there was "a clear operational plan" to
recapture the areas of the Jaffna peninsula that the army had lost
to the LTTE, but said she would not venture to mention a time
frame for the operation.
</P>
<P>
The president said she will press ahead with her new
constitution aimed at ending the 17-year civil war with or without
the participation of the LTTE rebels who have been fighting for a
separate state for minority Tamils in Sri Lanka's north and east.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels have been engaged in a ferocious assault over
the past two months in a bid to retake their former stronghold of
Jaffna.
</P>
<P>
However, only sporadic fighting has been reported for the past
week as the government has rushed new weapons and reinforcements
to Jaffna to beef up the defenses.
</P>
<P>
A defense ministry spokesman said the LTTE rebels might be
trying to regroup after having lost an estimated 200 to 250
fighters in the past fortnight. 
</P>
</TEXT>
