<DOCNO> XIE20000605.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Major Rivers, Lakes Remain Polluted: Bulletin (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 5 (Xinhua) -- China said today most of its major
rivers and lakes remained seriously polluted last year despite a
nationwide campaign to cut water pollution in the past years.
</P>
<P>
To curb the worsening water pollution, China has closed tens
of thousands of small and medium-sized polluting firms in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
In a bulletin issued today on China's environmental situation
in 1999, the State Environmental Protection Administration (SEPA)
said serious water pollution is common in the country's major
rivers.
</P>
<P>
Of China's seven major rivers, the Liaohe River in the
northeast and the Haihe River in the north are seriously polluted,
and the Huaihe River in the east is in poor condition, the
bulletin said.
</P>
<P>
And the quality of water in northern China's Yellow River, the
country's second longest, is worsening, it said, adding that the
Yellow River was affected by both a water shortage and water
pollution last year.
</P>
<P>
It said the river dried up for a total of 42 days last year,
95 days less than in 1998, while water rated as Class V or Class V+
-- the highest level of pollution -- was found in 63 percent of
the water sampled from 114 different spots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000605.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Major Rivers, Lakes Remain Polluted: Bulletin (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
The quality of water in the Songhua River in northeast China is
fairly good, while that of the Pearl River in south China, with
the exception of the section of Guangzhou, and of the Yangtze
River, is generally good, it said.
</P>
<P>
Serious pollution remains in the three major lakes in China,
with Class V or Class V+ water accounting for half of the sampled
water.
</P>
<P>
The three lakes are Taihu Lake near Shanghai, Dianchi Lake in
southwest China's Yunnan Province, and Chaohu Lake in east China's
Anhui Province, the bulletin said.
</P>
<P>
The outlook for the Liaohe River is much worse, where 70
percent of the sampled water from 52 water quality monitoring
stations is classified as Class V+, according to the bulletin.
</P>
<P>
China discharged a total of 40.1 billion tons of waste water
last year, up from 39.5 billion tons in the previous year, while
the chemical oxygen demand (COD) materials it contained decreased
by 7.2 percent over the previous year to 13.8 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The COD materials deplete oxygen in the water, thus harming
marine life.
</P>
<P>
It said 87 percent of the industrial waste water discharged by
major polluting township enterprises and firms at the country
level or above is treated, while 66 percent of the discharged
water was up to the discharge standards set by the state and local
governments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
