<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Possible Early Election Causes Tension Among Turkish Cabinet Partners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The decision by deputies of the
ruling partner Nationalist Action Party (MHP) to file a corruption
charge against Mesut Yilmaz, leader of another coalition partner
Motherland Party (ANAP), to the Supreme Court highlighted a serious
crisis in the tripartite cabinet led by Prime Minister Bulent
Ecevit.
</P>
<P>
The possibility of an early election was a major factor in the
decision by the MHP deputies, who serve in the parliamentary
commission investigating allegations about the former prime
minister's graft in selling a state-owned plot, Turkish Daily News
reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The possibility of an early election emerged as the
Constitutional Court is about to decide in October whether the pro-
Islamic opposition Virtue Party (FP) is the successor to the banned
Islamic Welfare Party.
</P>
<P>
If the court makes a "yes" verdict, the FP will be closed and 70
of the 103 FP deputies in the parliament will be dismissed.
</P>
<P>
According to the Constitution, if 5 percent (about 28) of the
550-member parliament are absent, the country should be forced into
an early parliament election within three months.
</P>
<P>
Due to the recent crisis, Yilmaz had to postpone his intention
of serving as a deputy prime minister in the government set up by
the Ecevit-led Democratic Left Party (DSP), the MHP and ANAP in
last May. In his reaction, Yilmaz directed harsh statements of
mistrust toward the MHP, threatening to withdraw from the cabinet
if the decision against him is approved by the full parliament.
</P>
<P>
In response, MHP leader and Deputy Prime Minister Devlet Bahceli
said that the actions of government and parliament are two
different missions and must not affect each other.
</P>
<P>
It was speculated that the MHP and the ANAP are trying to taint
the reputation of each other as part of their election strategy as
the ANAP is eyeing for the nationalist and conservative votes,
which the MHP is also wooing, in the absence of the FP.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts said the corruption allegations against Yilmaz
will be on the agenda of the Supreme Court, which will prevent the
ANAP leader from having a place in the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Due to the parliament's heavy agenda, it seems unlikely that it
will debate Yilmaz's case before the summer recess. The decision to
bring Yilmaz to the Supreme Court will be discussed in the full
parliament after its opening scheduled in October.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz, who believes the delay will cause harm to his party, is
trying to force its coalition partners to vote on the commission's
decision before parliament's recess.
</P>
<P>
If he succeeds, the MHP will be at a crossroad: they will either
send Yilmaz to the Supreme Court and face the possibility of
toppling the coalition government, or clear Yilmaz of the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz was getting the early harvest of this pressure on his
partners. Ecevit, who has attached importance to the cabinet's
stability, has voiced his concern about MHP's move.
</P>
<P>
It was expected that the parliament might have an early debate
of Yilmaz's case, if Ecevit maintains his position toward a cabinet
in unity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
