<HEADLINE> Germany to Receive 400 Former Pro-Israeli Militiamen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Germany will receive 400 former
South Lebanon Army (SLA) militiamen and their family members and
allow them to settle in Germany, German Foreign Minister Joschka
Fischer said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters after his meeting with Israeli Foreign
Minister David Levy, Fischer said the decision of his government is
purely out of humanitarian considerations.
</P>
<P>
Israel completed its troop withdrawal from south Lebanon on May
24 and it said that over 6,000 former pro-Israel SLA members and
their family members entered Israel along with Israel's pullout in
fear of reprisal from Lebanese guerrillas who had been fighting to
end Israeli occupation in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Fischer, who arrived here on Saturday for a three-day working
visit, was updated by Levy on the latest development of the Middle
East peace process and Israel's troop withdrawal from south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
During the Monday meeting, the two also discussed various ideas
on advancing bilateral Israeli-German relations and relations
between Israel and the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Fischer is also scheduled to hold talks later in the evening
with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak. 
</P>
