<HEADLINE> Debate on Lifting Former Israeli Minister's Immunity Postponed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli Knesset (parliament)
House Committee on Monday decided to put off for a month its debate
on stripping former Transport Minister Yitzhak Mordechai of the
parliamentary immunity to allow sexual harrassment charges to be
brought against him.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai requested the delay in order to decide whether he
wants to appeal before the attorney general in a hearing.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai, also the former chair of the Center Party which holds
six seats in the Knesset, submitted his resignation at the end of
May following Attorney General Elyakim Rubinstein's ruling that he
had sexually assaulted three women over the past eight years.
</P>
<P>
The attorney general has also called for stripping Mordechai's
immunity as Knesset member to pave the way for him to be put on
trial. If convicted, Mordechai could face up to seven years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the 55-year-old retired general has already received a
one-week delay to consider whether to attend the hearing.
</P>
<P>
Following Mordechai's resignation, Tourism Minister Amnon
Lipkin-Shahak has been appointed the new Center Party chair. He is
also to be named the Transport Minister in replacement of
Mordechai, who took a leave of office in early March following the
start of police investigation into allegations against him.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Ehud Barak has intended to place the Center
Party's new No. 2 man, Knesset (parliament) member Dan Meridor,
into the post of Tourism Minister. His negotiations with Meridor
have yielded no results so far.
</P>
<P>
Meridor, chairman of the Knesset Foreign Affairs and Defense
Committee, has reservations about the assignment as he sets his
sights on other posts such as the Justice Ministry portfolio now
held by Yossi Beilin of Barak's One Israel party. Meridor is also
said to be interested in receiving the defense portfolio, now held
by Barak.
</P>
<P>
There have been reports that Barak may use the opportunity of
Mordechai's resignation to reshuffle the cabinet in view of Housing
Minister Yitzhak Levy's intention to quit the government over the
handover of the Arab village Abu Dis just outside Jerusalem to full
Palestinian control. Levy is from the conservative National
Religious Party which has five representations in the Knesset.
</P>
<P>
Another vacancy in the cabinet is also likely to be created as
Regional Cooperation Minister Shimon Peres has become the leading
candidate for presidency.
</P>
<P>
Barak's aids have indicated that the prime minister is eager for
Meridor to take the Tourism offer, and that he plans to assign
Meridor, a close friend of his, to the ministerial team responsible
for advanced stages of negotiations with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
In case Meridor turns down the Tourism portfolio proposal, the
same offer will be put to the Center Party's next highest-ranking
figure, Knesset member Ronim Milo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
