<DOCNO> XIE20000605.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Makes Efforts to Protect Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Zambian Environment Minister Ben
Mwila said here Monday that the efforts in his country to protect
environment had achieved some good results.
</P>
<P>
Marking the World Environment Day which falls on June 5, he
said that Zambia's most pressing environmental problems include
air and water pollution, waste disposal, inadequate sanitation,
land and wetland degradation and wildlife depletion.
</P>
<P>
He said his country had worked out standards and regulations to
control air pollution. The Environmental Council of Zambia is
empowered to regulate emissions and put procedures for monitoring
pollution from industry.
</P>
<P>
He said the government had developed regulations for the
importation, handling, production and storage of pesticides and
will ensure that only registered chemicals are brought in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Although Zambia has a forest cover of about 60 percent of its
land, this resource is quickly being depleted owing to increased
population as well as needs for firewood, timber and farmland, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"Conservatively, the annual rate of deforestation has been
estimated at about 250,000 to 300,000 hectares. My ministry is
determined to fight this scourge through the provision of forest
policies that are conducive to sustainable forest management,"
said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Zambia is endowed with a number of wetlands rich in
biodiversity, which are threatened with degradation as a result of
draining them for settlement and agriculture.
</P>
<P>
He said the government is preparing a wetland policy to guide
the utilization of the wetland.
</P>
<P>
He said poaching posed the most serious threat to wildlife
conservation, and habitat destruction from mining, logging,
agriculture and human settlements are further exacerbating the
situation leading to disappearance of black rhino and near
disappearance of elephants in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
