<DOCNO> XIE20000605.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ageing to Exert Impact on Pensions: World Bank Economist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 5 (Xinhua) -- A rapidly ageing population
structure will place pressure on the sustainability of retirement
funding, top World Bank economist Estelle James said in South
Africa on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Institute of Retirement Funds' annual
conference in Cape Town, she said South Africa had a rapidly
ageing urban population.
</P>
<P>
By 2030 the proportion of the world's population that was over
the age of 60 would practically double, and this trend was
particularly strong in developing countries, she was quoted as
saying by the South African Press Association.
</P>
<P>
She said South Africa should follow the international move
toward a multi-pillared retirement structure.
</P>
<P>
In South Africa, company retirement funding was often voluntary
and largely only taken up by the top third of the population.
</P>
<P>
The system would be under pressure if the urban lower middle
class increase.
</P>
<P>
James recommended that this private sector retirement funding
be made mandatory and preferably structured on a defined
contribution basis.
</P>
<P>
This would enhance sustainability and economic growth and guard
against benefit promises that were too high and tax increases as
the population aged, she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
