<HEADLINE> Rival Leaders of Nigerian Senate Reach Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The two opposing camps in Nigerian
Senate have agreed to reconvene the upper house of parliament on
Tuesday, local press reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement between Senate President Chuba Okadigbo and his
deputy Alhaji Abubakar was brokered by President Olusegun
Obasanjo's ruling People' s Democratic Party in a meeting held in
the capital Abuja on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The senate is to discuss the supplementary bill for year 2000
budget and a bill on the development of the country' s oil
producing Niger delta region.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar is spearheading moves to topple the senate president,
accusing Okadigbo of lacking personal integrity.
</P>
<P>
The country's capital saw a surprising drama last week when the
maces in the senate chamber, indispensable for a session, were
missing and police forced into Okadigbo's residence to search for
them.
</P>
<P>
Okadigbo announced last week to adjourned the upper house until
July 7. Some senators led by the vice senate president criticized
the decision as trying to delay the debating of some issues of
vital importance.
</P>
<P>
President Obasanjo has repeatedly criticized the senate for the
constant delays in passing important bills, such as the
anti-corruption bill and the 2000 federal budget.
</P>
<P>
The senators on the other hand accused President Obasanjo of
acting unilaterally on issues that require the approval of the
senate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
