<HEADLINE> Seoul-Pyongyang Satellite Transmission Successfully Tested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 5 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's advance team preparing
for next week's inter-Korean summit in Pyongyang Monday
successfully tested the transmission of news through a satellite
news gathering system to Seoul.
</P>
<P>
The test transmission was sent out from Pyongyang for 38
minutes from 3:20 p.m. local time, and all local television
stations have received the broadcasts in good condition.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time that visual and audio signals were
transmitted by the satellite system from North to South on the
Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
The visual transmissions were relayed to each television
station through the Kwangjang satellite station in Seoul.
</P>
<P>
The press team from South Korea is expected to give live
coverage of the summit between South Korean President Kim Dae-jung
and Democratic People's Republic of Korea leader Kim Jung Il on
June 12-14 in Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement, a 50-member South Korean press team will
cover the first ever inter-Korean summit since the Korean
Peninsula was divided half a century ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
