<HEADLINE> HK Issues Consultation Paper on Domain Names Management </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region government Monday published a consultation
paper on the proposed arrangements for the administration and
assignment of Internet domain names and Internet protocol (IP)
addresses in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The paper was produced by a task force set up under the
Information Infrastructure Advisory Committee (IIAC) in October
1999 to review the administration and assignment of Internet
domain names and IP addresses.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the task force, Charles Kao, told a press
conference, "In reviewing the subject, we have carefully studied
the existing arrangements in Hong Kong and also the practices in
other economies."
</P>
<P>
The major recommendations of the task force include setting up
a new policy-making and administrative body, comprising members
from different sectors, to assume the overall responsibility for
Internet domain names administration in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The task force believed that more flexibility should be
provided in the registration of .hk domain names and companies and
organizations should be allowed to register more than one domain
name. Domain names ending with .hk should in principle be
transferable on valid grounds and registration by individuals in
Hong Kong should be allowed, it said.
</P>
<P>
The task force also suggested that an alternative dispute
resolution mechanism should be established to strengthen the
administrative measures on domain names dispute resolution.
</P>
<P>
As of April 2000, the number of domain names in Hong Kong
ending with .hk is around 37,000 whereas that of monthly new
applications exceeds 2,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000605.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs from
Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt and Japan signed on Sunday a number of agreements
by which the latter will offer Egypt three grants estimated at 45
million U.S. dollars to finance projects in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The first agreement concerns an additional grant to Ferdan
Bridge on the Suez Canal which is set to be concluded in October
2001. The additional grant is aiming to accelerate the construction
of the bridge which links Africa and Asia and help fulfill
comprehensive development in the Sinai peninsula.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- The Yemeni Saba Trade and Contracting Company announced
the conclusion of Jabal Sabr road in Taaz city. The road was
financed by a grant from Saudi Minister of Defense and Aviation,
Prince Sultan Ibn Abdul-Aziz.
</P>
<P>
The 16-kilometer road starts from Taaz up to the peak of Sabr
Mountain at a height of 3,060 meters, said the company's board
chairman Abdel Haq Saed.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Oman has decided to raise the May retroactive price
of its crude oil by 3.71 dollars to 26.66 dollars per barrel, an
oil and gas ministry official said.
</P>
<P>
Rashed bin Khalid Al-Birwani, advisor for marketing affairs at
the ministry, said the decision was taken due to the rise in world
oil prices.
</P>
<P>
He noted the price for April was 22.95 dollars per barrel.
</P>
<P>
Oman pumps about 900,000 barrels of crude oil a day.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Oman has made a remark that it would export 260,000
cubic metres of liquefied natural gas (LNG) to the United States,
with the first delivery scheduled in July.
</P>
<P>
"It is a short-term agreement with Coral Energy to deliver two
cargoes of liquefied natural gas in July and August," Nasser Al
Balushi, LNG spokesman in the ministry of oil and gas said.
</P>
<P>
Oman shipped its first cargo of liquefied natural gas in April
to South Korea from the Oman LNG terminal in the eastern coastal
city of Sur.
</P>
<P>
Oman LNG earlier said it would start LNG exports to Spain in the
fourth quarter of 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
