<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodia, Thailand Open Border Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia and Thailand opened
talks here Monday in an effort to resolve their long-lasting
border conflict.
</P>
<P>
At the talks, both sides expressed their optimism that the
border conflict will be resolved.
</P>
<P>
Sukhumbhand Paribatra, Thai deputy foreign minister, led the
Thai delegation while his Cambodian counterpart, Var Kimhong,
headed the Cambodian side.
</P>
<P>
This is the second meeting of the Cambodian-Thai Joint
Commission on Demarcation of Land Boundary. The first one was held
in Thailand last year.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia claims that Thailand has encroached some parts of its
803-kilometer borderlines in its northern and western parts.
</P>
<P>
At least four provinces of Koh Kong, Pursat, Battambang and
Banteay Meanchey have been invaded by Thailand, Cambodia charged
in a report issued Monday before the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Var Kimhong, chief of the Cambodian side, said the meeting will
last until Wednesday and a memorandum of understanding will be
signed by the time.
</P>
<P>
The meeting takes place just days ahead of Thai Prime Minister
Chuan Leekpai's visit to Cambodia from June 14 to 16.
</P>
<P>
The border demarcation between the two countries was determined
in the late 1910s during the French colonial regime in which 73
border posts were erected, but it is unclear how many of them
remain today, Var Kimhong told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"The delay in the examination on the border conflict was caused
by three decades of civil war, insecurity along the border and
land mines," he said.
</P>
<P>
Var Kimhong, however, said the border checking will be started
by the end of the year if the two sides agree at this meeting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
