<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Nations Urged to Meet Challenges With Improved Ability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Developing countries in the Asian-
Pacific region should strengthen their ability to meet numerous
challenges ahead, senior officials from countries in the region
and the United Nations said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the ministerial meeting of the 56th session of the
U.N.Economic and Social Commission for Asia and the Pacific (ESCAP)
, the officials stressed that for these countries, there is no
other choice but to better prepare themselves for all the incoming
challenges of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai said in his inaugural address
to the meeting, held here from June 5 to 7, that although Asia is
expected to continue to be the world's fastest growing region,this
does not mean the end of concerns and challenges.
</P>
<P>
"Here, it is imperative that we strengthen our respective
national capacities," he stressed. "In short, we have to improve
our ability to compete."
</P>
<P>
Thai Foreign Minister Surin Pitsuwan and senior officials from
other countries in the Asian-Pacific region also urged the
developing countries in the region to strengthen their capacity
and find ways and means to face the big challenges.
</P>
<P>
In a written message to the meeting, U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan pointed out that the Asian-Pacific region is now facing
"a range of complex and pressing issues" and "the overarching
challenge is to manage the risks and seize the opportunities of
globalization."
</P>
<P>
Adrianus Mooy, U.N. under-secretary-general and ESCAP executive
secretary, promised at the meeting that the ESCAP remains
committed to assisting the region's developing countries in
building their capacity.
</P>
<P>
"One of the principal purposes of this forum is to see how best
we can address these challenges collectively with a view to
accelerating the pace of growth and dealing with complex social
issues," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
