<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chirac to Speak on Reforming Presidential Term </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 5 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac will
make a televised speech Monday evening on reforming the
presidential term from seven years to five years.
</P>
<P>
So far Chirac has not publicly given his definite view on
shortening the presidential term, but he is widely expected to
approve such a reform.
</P>
<P>
The proposal to shorten the presidential term was first made on
May 10 by former President Valery Giscard d'Estaing, who said that
the seven-year term is outdated.
</P>
<P>
The seven-year presidential term was introduced into the
Constitution of the Fifth Republic in 1958 by President Charles de
Gaulle who intended to strengthen the power of the chief of state.
</P>
<P>
A draft law on reforming the presidential term, which should be
presented by Chirac and the government jointly, would be put to
vote either through a referendum or through a congressional voting
by the two chambers of the parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000605.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BIS: China Grows Faster Than Other Asian Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BASEL, SWITZERLAND, June 5 (Xinhua) -- China has grown faster
than other Asian countries although output growth has been on a
slowing trend for several years, the Bank for International
Settlements (BIS) said in its 70th annual report published here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The report, covering the period between April 1999 and March
2000, said that the authorities in China sought to ease monetary
conditions by lowering nominal interest rates and cutting reserve
requirements while confronted with falling prices and rising
unemployment.
</P>
<P>
"They also directed banks to increase credit for infrastructure,
housing and exports, provide more working capital to state-owned
enterprises and grant more consumer credit," the BIS said.
</P>
<P>
In China, exports were stimulated in the latter half of 1999 by
an increase in tax rebates, according to the BIS. Partly as a
result of a crackdown on smuggling, there was a particularly large
rise in reported imports in China.
</P>
<P>
Various patterns of restructuring are also beginning to emerge
in China, where the state-owned enterprise (SOE) reform agenda has
focused on improving management and governance, according to the
BIS report. Large SOEs are being corporatized and many are forming
joint ventures with foreign investors, while small SOEs are
quickly moving out of the state sector, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000605.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sweden Registers Significant Drop in Rates of Young Smokers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The rates of young smokers in
Sweden have dropped sharply during the past 20 years, according to
a report released Monday by the country's central statistics
bureau.
</P>
<P>
The rate of female daily smokers aged 16 to 24 fell to 18
percent in 1998 from 37 percent in 1980, while that of the male
daily smokers in the same age bracket went down to 10 percent in
1998 from 28 percent in 1980, said the report.
</P>
<P>
In the age group between 25 and 34, the rate of female daily
smokers dropped to 20 percent in 1998 from 41 percent in 1980, and
that of male daily smokers dropped to 13 percent from 45 percent.
</P>
<P>
The bureau said fewer and fewer people are growing addicted to
smoking while more and more people are giving up the habit in
Sweden. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000605.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rafter Sets for Wimbledon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
PARIS, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Australian star Pat Rafter set to
play at Wimbledon, despite pulling out of the French Open men's
doubles in order to rest his troublesome shoulder, reports said on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Rafter, who was partnering compatriot Lleyton Hewitt said that
while his shoulder remains "tender" it will not prevent him from
playing at Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
The Queenslander has played little competitive tennis this
year after arthroscopic surgery last October sidelined him for six
months, reports said. 
</P>
