<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs from
the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli import of durable goods continued to
accelerate in May with automobile imports up 17 percent from the
previous month and up 82 percent compared to May 1999.
</P>
<P>
Figures released by the Central Bureau of Statistics on Monday
indicated that 59,335 passenger vehicles were brought into Israel
during the first five months of 2000, representing a total value of
535.8 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The total amount of durable goods imported during the months of
January through May hit 629.9 million dollars, versus 466.8 million
dollars during the same period in 1999 -- an increase of 35
percent.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Israel Bar Association is expected to allow its
members to advertise their offices, fees and specializations in the
national, local and professional press.
</P>
<P>
The National Council of the association is expected to meet soon
to discuss the recommendations of an internal association committee
on revising the rules of ethics that guide lawyers in advertizing.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- El Al Israel Airlines lost 36 million dollars
during the first quarter of 2000 and expects to finish the year
with a loss of 50 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The substantial first-quarter loss is attributable to high fuel
prices. The summer season is expected to be "balanced," but
projections for the latter part of the year are not positive.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Trade between the United Arab Emirates and Japan in
1999 rose by 1.96 percent to 11.3 billion dollars compared with 11.
1 billion dollars in 1998, powered by the surge in crude oil
prices, according to a report issued by Japanese External Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
The rise in UAE's exports helped shore up trade, in spite of a
decline in Japan's exports to the UAE. Exports from the UAE cover
nearly 78 percent of Japan-UAE trade.
</P>
<P>
The report also indicated the UAE is Japan's ninth largest
supplier of products and services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
