<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Environment Protection Makes Headway in Ankara By Huai Chengbo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- This year's World Environment Day on
June 5 is being marked in Turkey with tangible progress in
environmental protection in the country's capital of Ankara.
</P>
<P>
With a population of nearly four million and the increasing
expansion of the municipalities, pressure has been building up on
the authorities to grapple with a variety of problems accompanying
industrialization and modernization.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to a German government loan, the construction of Ankara
central wastewater treatment plant, located 40 kilometers from the
city center, was undertaken by former Ankara Greater Municipality
Mayor Murat Karayalcin and put into operation by current Ankara
Mayor Melih Gokcek.
</P>
<P>
The huge 200-million-U.S. dollar complex, the fourth biggest in
the world, has made the first step in a city designed to ease
pollution and protect the environment in line with the European
Union standard.
</P>
<P>
The wastewater treatment plant cleans 90 percent of 750,000
cubic meters of domestic and industrial wastewater the city
produces in a 10-hour period daily and provides 24-hour service
each day yearly.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, another thorny environmental issue is being solved.
</P>
<P>
Recently, the Mamak municipality and the Greater Ankara
municipality have agreed to move the Mamak garbage dump, which has
been in use for 20 years and is spread close to the city center, to
Sincan on the western outskirts of the capital. New modern facility
will reportedly open in August this year.
</P>
<P>
Mayor Gokcek has promised that the Mamak dump will be
transformed and trees planted to create a big park in its place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
