<HEADLINE> IMF Optimistic Over Indonesia's Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Managing Director of the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) Horst Koehler said here Monday
that Indonesia's economy will grow by 4 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
He also urged the Indonesian government to accelerate the
implementation of the country's economic recovery program
contained in a letter of intent between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
"The economic recovery program that was adopted by the
government is working and you can see it in certain
accomplishments, particularly you can see that the economic growth
is coming back. And the experts of the IMF expect that for
Indonesia the economy will grow by 4 percent,"Koehler told a press
conference here before leaving for India as a part of his Asia
tour.
</P>
<P>
"That is of course not enough to solve every of all huge
problems (in Indonesia), but it is a good and an encouraging
starting point," Koehler added.
</P>
<P>
Koehler arrived here on Sunday for a two-day visit, during
which he met with President Abdurrahman Wahid, Vice President
Megawati Soekarnoputeri, Speaker of the Indonesian Parliament
Akbar Tandjung, Minister of Finance Bambang Sudibyo and other
government officials.
</P>
<P>
He said, "I came here to also personally reconfirm, reassure
that we are here to support, to help, we are not here to lecture (
the Indonesian government) but we give advice, frank advice,
because we feel that is our duty," Koehler added.
</P>
<P>
He also urged the Indonesian people to work hand in hand to
make the economic recovery program successful.
</P>
<P>
Koehler also said President Wahid will closely monitor the
implementation of the economic recovery program.
</P>
<P>
"That is good news particularly for investors, because they
know that the direction (of economic recovery) is clear and is
fully backed by the president and his economic team," he said.
</P>
<P>
But Koehler cautioned the Indonesian Banking Restructuring
Agency (IBRA), an agency under the control of the Ministry of
Finance, to accelerate the privatization process to stimulate
economic dynamics.
</P>
<P>
"The president and I agree to accelerate the decision-making
process in the IBRA. That means to sell assets to restructure(
ailing enterprises) in order to stimulate investment and economic
dynamics. Further delay in the process of asset sales and the
restructuring of enterprises would lead to the deterioration of
asset values of IBRA," Koehler said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
