<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Take Action Against Papua Separatists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Minister of Law and
Legal Affairs Yusril Ihza Mahendra said here Monday that the
government will discuss the results of the Papua National Congress
and may consider to take legal actions against separatists there.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters at the parliament building, Mahendra said,
"I think that is a serious problem. We should discuss such a
problem in a cabinet meeting. We will consider what steps we are
going to take to deal with that," Mahendra said.
</P>
<P>
"We need to launch an investigation into those involved in the
declaration of independence in the course of the Papua National
Congress.We should also make sure whether or not they have broken
law. If yes,the government should take legal actions against them,
" he added.
</P>
<P>
"Hopefully, there will be same opinions on what is happening in
Papua Province. I also hope there will be a same attitude of the
cabinet to deal with this problem."
</P>
<P>
The week-long Papua National Congress ended on Sunday in
Jayapura,capital of Papua Province, with the adoption of a
resolution declaring Papua's incorporation into Indonesia in the
1960s invalid and stating that the resource-rich province is an
independence state.
</P>
<P>
President Abdurrahman Wahid has vowed to take stern measures
toward all activities aimed at declaring an independent Papua.
</P>
<P>
Papua is the largest island in Indonesia with a population of
about 2 million.
</P>
<P>
In 1963, the then President Sukarno led Indonesia's fight to
regain the mineral-rich territory from the Netherlands. It was
officially integrated into Indonesia after a U.N.-sponsored
plebiscite in 1969.
</P>
</TEXT>
