<HEADLINE> Tanzania Worried about Disposal of Expired Pesticides </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania is worried about
seeking financial aid to dispose of about 960 tons of expired
pesticides scattered all over the country, local newspapers
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania needs donation of some 3.84 million U.S. dollars to
dispose of the expired pesticides in more than 300 sites, an
official was quoted as saying at a one-day seminar on control of
pesticides importation in Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The Registrar of Pesticides Jonathan Akhabuhaya told the
seminar held in Tanga in the eastern coast that a two-year survey
conducted by a waste management committee formed by the government
showed that most of the expired pesticides were found in the
cotton-growing regions.
</P>
<P>
The registrar also noted that the expired pesticides were
either imported by crop authorities or were in the form of
assistance given by donors to farmers.
</P>
<P>
"Others were imported by unscrupulous businessmen who failed to
sell all their pesticides while some belonged to centers
experimenting on new pesticides," he added.
</P>
<P>
Akhabuhaya said that as a proposal seeking funds to destroy the
 pesticides had already been prepared and sent to potential
donors, the Netherlands had expressed interest in funding the
project.
</P>
<P>
He challenged the customs officers to co-operate closely in
fighting against illegal importation of pesticides so that
Tanzania was not turned into a dumping ground for expired or
sub-standard chemicals.
</P>
<P>
Officials at the seminar said that the free market was being
taken as an excuse to import unregistered and sub-standard
pesticides that could cause untold loss to the country by
adversely affecting crops and livestock and becoming health
hazards to humans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
