<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia to Lose One Percent of Revenue Under FTA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Zambia will only lose one percent of
its revenue once the country joins Common Market for Eastern and
Southern Africa (COMESA) Free Trade Area (FTA) in October this
year, a senior official at COMESA center said.
</P>
<P>
Charles Chanthunya, Director of Trade, Customs and Monetary
Affairs at the center, made the remarks in an interview with
Zambia Daily Mail newspaper published on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Currently, COMESA regional market attracts 25 percent of
Zambia's exports and this is with duty, so we expect the market to
increase when duty is lifted. As for losing revenue, our research
shows that Zambia would lose one percent or less," Chanthunya
said.
</P>
<P>
Chanthunya said there was a possible increase in value added
tax once the country entered FTA as the government had no way of
raising revenue from duty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
