<DOCNO> XIE20000605.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BIS: World Economic Growth Faster Than Expected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BASEL, SWITZERLAND, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Growth rates in most
parts of the world in the period between April 1999 and March 2000
were significantly faster than expected, the Bank for
International Settlements (BIS) said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
In the annual report published on the occasion of its 70th
annual general meeting, the Basel-based BIS said that the world
real GDP outcome during the period under review was 2.6 percent,
tremendously higher than its forecast of 1.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Inflation stayed very low in most industrial and emerging
market countries, while economic growth remained high in the
United States, picked up in Europe and began to recover later in
the year in Latin America, according to the BIS report.
</P>
<P>
The BIS said that the turnaround in the fortunes of several
crisis-hit East Asian countries was nothing short of remarkable,
and China and India continued to expand at high rates. Even in
Japan, there were signs that the worst might be over.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, there were increasing grounds for believing that this
might be a longer-term trend based on some combination of
continuing deregulation, new technology and capital deepening in
many countries.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the BIS pointed out that significant
macroeconomic imbalances could be identified. In countries like
the United States where the expansion was furthest advanced,
underlying inflationary pressures were of increasing concern, as
were rising debt levels.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, financial markets returned to risk-taking with
increasing eagerness, according to the BIS. Prices of many stocks,
especially in the technology sector, reached new highs and
borrowing spreads on private debt securities eased gradually
despite episodes of liquidity pressure, as long-term interest
rates rose.
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter of 2000, it said, both equity and credit
markets wavered, especially in the United States, reflecting
concerns about excessive valuations, uncertainty about the extent
and impact of monetary tightening and supply development in U.S.
government debt.
</P>
<P>
Historically high current account imbalances and global stock
market valuations went hand in hand with large and often volatile
movements in the value of major currencies, said the BIS.
</P>
<P>
In its conclusion, the BIS cautioned, "There remains
considerable uncertainty as to whether the global economy is at
the beginning of a long boom, driven by technology and
deregulation, or whether it is significantly exposed to the
possibility of a downturn through which long-standing
macroeconomic imbalances will eventually be resolved."
</P>
<P>
It said that there was also an unusual degree of uncertainty
about how financial markets which have been evolving rapidly,
might react to possibly adverse macroeconomic shocks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000605.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Soar in Tokyo on Wall Street Surge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices soared in Tokyo Monday,
helped by last Friday's surge on Wall Street, with the benchmark
Nikkei index closing above 17,000 for the first time in 12 trading
days.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange jumped 401.73 points, or 2.39
percent, from last Friday's close to end at 17,201.79.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, climbed 38.99 points, or 2.51 percent, to 1,
595.44.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section decreased to 666.76 million
shares from last Friday's 783.50 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Mitsubishi Heavy Industries was the day's volume leader.
</P>
<P>
High-priced information and technology drew active buying after
New York's technology-heavy NASDAQ composite index marked its
third-largest one-day point rise, leading overall share prices up.
</P>
<P>
Brokerage houses, trading firms and automakers also saw large
gains.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, electric power and gas firms, banks and real estate
issues faced selling.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, gainers outnumbered
losers 817 to 432, while 142 issues closed unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
