<HEADLINE> Jayasinghe Qualifies for Olympic Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
COLOMBO, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's sprinter Susanthika
Jayasinghe has qualified for the Asian Games and the Olympic Games
squad but with a disappointing time in the 100m race, according to
reports on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Jayasinghe clocked 11.39 seconds, at a two-day weekend
selection meet, 0.22 seconds slower than when she bagged gold at
an IAAF Japan Grand Prix last year, reports said.
</P>
<P>
The 1997 World Championship 200m silver medallist opted out of
the longer spring here, saying the competition was not good enough.
</P>
<P>
Jayasinghe recently returned from the United States where she
has been training following serious differences with Sri Lankan
sports authorities whom she accused of trying to ruin her career.
</P>
<P>
In October last year, the International Amateur Athletics
Federation (IAAF) abandoned its case against Jayasinghe who had
been accused of taking a banned substance, nandrolone.
</P>
<P>
The IAAF explained there were difficulties in making a legal
case, and that there were strong doubts that the Sri Lankan had
breached anti-doping rules.
</P>
<P>
Jayasinghe had been banned after testing positive to taking
the banned steriod in April 1998, but the suspension was lifted
four months later.  
</P>
</TEXT>
