<HEADLINE> Sadyrin Takes over Struggling CSKA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Former Russia coach Pavel Sadyrin,
who has resigned from his Uzbekistan coach's job, will take over
struggling premier division side CSKA Moscow, accroding to club
officials Monday.
</P>
<P>
The 57-year-old Sadyrin, who guided Russia in the 1994 World
Cup finals, had been with the Uzbek national team for the last six
months. He succeeds Oleg Dolmatov who resigned last week after a
poor start to the season.
</P>
<P>
It is Sadyrin's third coaching stint at the army side. On his
first attempt, he guided them to the top flight in just one season
in 1989, then two years later, led them to a league and cup double.
</P>
<P>
But on his second, two years ago, Sadyrin was sacked by CSKA
management after a bitter dispute with the players.
</P>
<P>
CSKA are in 13th place in the 16-team premier division with
eight points from 10 matches. 
</P>
</TEXT>
