<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Appeal Court Rejects Anwar's Appeal on PM's Testimony </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's Court of Appeal
Monday rejected former Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim's
appeal against the High Court's ruling not to call Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad as a witness in his sodomy trial.
</P>
<P>
The court's president, Lamin Yunus, announced the court
decision after allowing preliminary objections raised by Attorney-
General Mohtar Abdullah, who led the prosecution team, pertaining
to the appeal.
</P>
<P>
After the court delivered its decision, Anwar's leading counsel
Christopher Fernando told reporters that the defense would appeal
to the Federal Court and the notice of appeal would be filed as
soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Justice Lamin also ordered Anwar's sodomy trial before High
Court judge Arifin Jaka to proceed. The sodomy trial was postponed
indefinitely by Arifin pending the disposal of the appeal.
</P>
<P>
Justice Arifin ruled earlier that to call Mahathir to testify
in the trial would be an abuse of the court process and it was his
duty to prevent such a thing from happening.
</P>
<P>
Anwar, 52, is jointly tried with his adopted brother Sukma
Darmawan Sasmitaat Madja, 39, on separate charges of sodomizing
his former family driver Azizan Abu Bakar.
</P>
<P>
Both Anwar and Sukma had applied to the court to have Mahathir
as a defense witness in his personal capacity.
</P>
<P>
Anwar is serving a six-year jail sentence upon conviction on
four counts of corrupt practice of interfering in police
investigations into allegations of his sexual misconduct.
</P>
<P>
Anwar, also the former finance minister, was dismissed from the
cabinet on September 2, 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
