<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Police to Update Drug Traffickers' List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian police is
working on an updated list of suspected drug traffickers in the
country in collaboration with South African and British
intelligence services.
</P>
<P>
The official Daily News on Monday quoted the Tanzanian Director
of Criminal Investigation Adadi Rajabu as saying that the police
is working closely with the South African and British intelligence
services in the fight against drug trafficking which has earned
the country a place on the blacklist of international
anti-narcotics agencies.
</P>
<P>
"We do not ignore information from any source. We work on them
before pouncing on the suspects," the police chief was quoted as
saying after chairing the eighth operational meeting on drugs for
East African heads of criminal investigation and anti-narcotics
units, which ended in Dar es Salaam last weekend.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Rajabu and his Kenyan counterpart Francis
Sang stressed that geographical position of Tanzania and Kenya is
convenient for drug trafficking to the southern part of Africa,
Europe and America.
</P>
<P>
The police officials admitted that good roads, long unpatrolled
coastal area and borders, plus the Dar es Salaam and Kilimanjaro
international airports in Tanzania, are major advantages for the
flourishing of drug trafficking in the region.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, some of the traffickers use Nairobi in
Kenya and Entebbe in Uganda as points of exit to Europe via the
Middle East. 
</P>
</TEXT>
