<HEADLINE> IMF to Audit Kenya on Reform Promises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) plans to conduct half-year audit on Kenya's economic reform
promises reached with donors for the release of 220 million U.S.
dollars in program support.
</P>
<P>
A high-ranking IMF official said the money would be released in
seven batches over a three-year period, with the first released
after the IMF board gives its nod, the East African weekly
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Under the arrangement, the Kenyan government is supposed to
publish, probably in mid-June, a set of documents setting forth
the pledges it has made to the IMF.
</P>
<P>
Last month, IMF officials held a three-week discussion with the
 Kenyan officials in Nairobi over the lending programs.
</P>
<P>
Following the talks, a recommendation for the release of
program support held up since 1997 is expected to be presented to
the IMF board next month.
</P>
<P>
The IMF suspended a 205-million-dollar loan to Kenya in July
1997 for reasons of poor governance and rampant corruption.
</P>
</TEXT>
