<HEADLINE> French Police Arrest Suspect for Sabotaging Railway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 5 (Xinhua) -- French police have arrested a man
suspected to have sabotaged a railway track and caused the
derailment of a train on Sunday, media reports said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Two persons were killed and 12 injured in the derailment of a
long-distance train in Chasse-sur-Rhone in southern France Sunday
morning.
</P>
<P>
Police detained on Sunday a 32-year-old Algerian man who
traveled from Paris to Chasse-sur-Rhone on Saturday and lived in a
hotel near the railway station of the town, according to the Le
Figaro daily.
</P>
<P>
The man, who lived and worked in the Paris region, was
suspected to belong to an Islamic militant group of Algeria, said
police.
</P>
<P>
His movement was under the watch of the Direction of
Surveillance of Territory, a security organ under the Interior
Ministry, according to Le Figaro.
</P>
<P>
Police have also found on the site of the accident a one-meter
long rail track which was believed to have been sabotaged,
according to a report by Agence France-Presse (AFP).
</P>
<P>
The National Anti-terrorist Division, a special security unit
of French police based in Paris, is now in charge of investigating
the accident, AFP quoted police sources as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
