<DOCNO> XIE20000605.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Reaffirms Readiness to Join U.N. Peacekeeping in Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 5 (Xinhua) -- France reaffirmed on Monday its
readiness to join an expanded United Nations peacekeeping
operation in Lebanon, on the condition that Lebanese government
troops are deployed in the southern border area.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine said in a radio
interview that France "does not hesitate at all" to send more
troops to Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations is preparing for an expanded peacekeeping
mission in Lebanon after Israel pulled out its troops from
Lebanon's southern border area last month.
</P>
<P>
"France does not hesitate at all. But when it is a question of
sending French soldiers in a situation which could become
uncontrollable or even dangerous, it is absolutely normal for the
French president and prime minister to raise all the questions,"
Vedrine told Radio-Television Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
"We remain technically ready, but politically the examination
is not finished because not all the conditions have been met," he
said.
</P>
<P>
France has 249 soldiers serving in the United Nations Interim
Force in Lebanon (UNFIL) deployed since 1978 in the Middle East
state.
</P>
<P>
The mandate of UNFIL should be renewed by the U.N. Security
Council at the end of July and its make-up is expected to be
reinforced from the present 4,500 to 7,900.
</P>
<P>
"The present UNFIL is there until the end of July and there is
no reason to express worry or impatience at the present stage,"
said the foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Lebanese government should "show the signs of
restoring its authority" in southern Lebanon by sending government
troops there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
