<HEADLINE> Shenyang's "Strange Slope" Becomes Tourism Attraction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, June 5 (Xinhua) -- A mysterious slope that hinders
vehicle operation in Shenyang, capital of northeast China's
Liaoning Province, is attracting more and more visitors since it
was discovered in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The 80-meter-long and 20-meter-wide mysterious slope, at the
western foot of the Maoshan Mountain in the Xinchengzi District of
Shenyang, runs from the west to the east. Drivers have to speed to
drive downward the slope and go with the breaker when drive upward,
otherwise the vehicle will accelerate on its own.
</P>
<P>
In the past decade, more than 4 million visitors including over
50,000 from overseas have visited the strange slope, its nearby
scenic spots and recreational facilities in the past decade.
</P>
</TEXT>
