<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Israeli newspapers Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Russia has undermined the anti-ballistic missile treaty by
passing on its technology to Middle East "rogue states," perhaps
putting Israel at a greater threat than ever before, a study
released by the Jerusalem Center for Public Affairs accused.
</P>
<P>
The study also suggested that it is in Israel's best interests
for the Anti-Ballistic Missile (ABM) treaty to be done away with or
altered, since its present framework is preventing Israel from
enhancing its missile defense.
</P>
<P>
The findings of the study came out as Russian President Vladimir
Putin hosted U.S. President Bill Clinton, who is seeking to alter
the ABM treaty because it restricts the range of anti-missile
defense.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak convened a meeting late
Sunday night to discuss the continuing coalition crisis with the
religious Shas party. Ministers Avraham Shochat, Yossi Beilin and
Shlomo Ben-Ami took part in the discussion.
</P>
<P>
Barak's meeting was held as negotiations continued between
Minister in Barak's Office Haim Ramon and Shas leaders about
revisions in the recovery plan for the party's education system.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations were resumed Sunday night after Shas spurned a
compromise proposal offered by Ramon last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- Twelve-year-old Aid Sharon returned safely to Israel on
Sunday, 10 months after being kidnapped on a visit to his father in
Moscow and held for millions of U.S. dollars in ransom.
</P>
<P>
Arriving at Ben-Gurion Airport along with his father Yossi and
Russian Interior Minister Vladimir Rushailo at 7 p.m., Sharon was
immediately brought to hospital for treatment for malnutrition and
dehydration.
</P>
<P>
In a dramatic televised raid, a Russian team rescued Sharon
Thursday night from a filthy basement in the southern Russian city
of Penza. The boy had been kept under harsh conditions, not seeing
daylight and subsisting on bread and water. Parts of two of the
boy's fingers had been cut off because his family did not pay the
ransom demanded.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak emphasized at Sunday's
cabinet meeting that the fact that Clinton is still United States
President constitutes a opportunity for Israel to reach an
agreement with the Palestinians now.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that Clinton, along with his European partners, is
prepared to invest billions of U.S. dollars in helping solve the
problems of refugees, water desalination, building a bridge between
Gaza and the West Bank, building a border fence, and other peace-
related projects.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright is due to meet Barak
Monday evening, after she arrives to lead the White House drive to
bring the prime minister and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
together in a summit with Clinton by the end of the month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
