<DOCNO> XIE20000605.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Mindanao Peace Process on Shaky Ground  By Pan Jiaxu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Challenges loom ahead as the
Philippine government and the rebel Moro Islamic Liberation (MILF)
are trying to find a "final solution" to the decades-old Mindanao
conflict.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, negotiation panels from both sides reportedly
agreed to meet again on June 28 to discuss and settle the issue of
the autonomy proposal presented by the government to the MILF, a
step said to meet the June 30 deadline imposed by President Joseph
Estrada.
</P>
<P>
Press reports quoted Estrada as saying that the current peace
talks, resumed on May 29 after months of suspension due to
escalating clashes between government troops and the MILF, will be
the "last chance" of the Muslim rebel group.
</P>
<P>
The government panel said the MILF, which has been fighting for
more than two decades for a separate Islamic state in Mindanao,
has "agreed in principle" to accept autonomy in the resumed peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
However, political observers said there stand a series of
unfavorable factors that might hamper the "final talks" to meet
the deadline for the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say the war that is raging on in Mindanao has
undermined the mutual trust -- sentiments which deem to be vital
to helping work out positive results in the forthcoming talks.
</P>
<P>
According to recent reports, the government has rejected a
cease-fire call made by the MILF although the two sides have
agreed to meet again.
</P>
<P>
Increasing its presence in Mindanao, the government troops have
totally surrounded the Abudakar Camp, the headquarters of the MILF,
in Maguindanao, west Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
In ongoing military attacks that have lasted more than a month,
government troops have overrun major MILF camps in the neighboring
provinces of North and South Lanaos.
</P>
<P>
Citing the intensified military pressure, the MILF raised
doubts over the government's sincerity in the peace talks, saying
the military option is not the right way to finalize a settlement
of the conflict in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
The government, however, complained that the MILF has played
too much tricks in the past by using a cease-fire statement as a
chance to restore its power buildup rather than to start sincere
talks.
</P>
<P>
"A lot of confidence were lost in the conflict," said Eliseo
Mercardo, chairman of an independent fact-finding committee which
is tasked to monitor the peace talks. Lack of confidence is the
major enemy of the peace talks, he added.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, observers said the intensified military campaign
might result in a destruction of the 15,000-strong MILF before any
peace pact is achieved.
</P>
<P>
Citing the feared risk, observers said that if the MILF
guerrillas vanished militarily, the group would simply splinter
away and they would boycott any peace accord between the
government and the MILF.
</P>
<P>
The observers even made further speculation that the
destruction of the MILF might result in the formation of bandit
groups like the Abu Sayyaf, which is holding 21 mostly foreign
hostages in Sulu and eight all-Filipino hostages in Basilan.
</P>
<P>
In that case, the observers said, any forging of a peace
agreement between the government and the MILF only means that more
"shoot and talk" tasks lie ahead.
</P>
<P>
In addition, how to keep a good balance between the mainstream
Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF) and the MILF is another
challenge to the government advocated autonomy.
</P>
<P>
Reports disclosed Monday that Governor Nur Misuari of the
Autonomous Region in Muslim Mindanao (ARMM) has been trying to
block the forging of a peace pact between the government and the
MILF.
</P>
<P>
Misuari, also chief of the former rebel group of the MNLF,
reportedly said during his recent trip to Saudi Arabia that the
government has delayed its full implementation of the Manila-MNLF
peace treaty signed in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Manila-MNLF treaty provided for an expansion of the ARMM to
cover 10 cities and 14 provinces in Mindanao. At present, the ARMM
consists only of the four provinces of Maguindanao, South Lanao,
Tawi-Tawi and Sulu.
</P>
<P>
Misuari's statement has been widely believed to be a caution on
the MILF, the breakaway faction of the MNLF, to boycott the
proposed autonomy.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts said that a separate autonomous region for the
MILF would include portions of the yet-to-be-expanded ARMM, adding
that the government proposal would inevitably arouse territorial
disputes between the MNLF and the MILF.
</P>
<P>
"The MILF will not agree to that (to be included in an expanded
ARMM)," MILF spokesman Eid Kabalu was reported as saying. "This is
not a joke ... It can not be done that way."
</P>
<P>
"They (the government) want to dictate the outcome of the
negotiation. On our part, we want a negotiated solution, otherwise
the problems will come again," the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
While noting the peace talks might bring hopes for a political
solution to the Mindanao conflict, analysts said that things could
become worse before they get better in the peace process, which is
set on a shaky ground. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000605.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
