<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fiji Military Hands Ultimatum to Coup Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Fiji's military government Monday
handed coup leader George Speight and his men an ultimatum to
release their hostages and lay down their guns, the Australian
Associated Press (AAP) reported.
</P>
<P>
The AAP said that in the army's strongest warning yet to the
rebel leader, military government head and army Commander Frank
Bainimarama said: "We will not entertain any more demands by
George Speight and his men."
</P>
<P>
Bainimarama was quoted as saying in a statement that talks to
try to free 31 government hostages held by Speight at gunpoint
since May 19 had reached deadlock.
</P>
<P>
He said Speight and his men would be granted an amnesty for the
seizure of Fiji's parliament and MPs including Fiji's first ethnic
Indian Prime Minister Mahendra Chaudhry.
</P>
<P>
But the military would not agree to demands that Speight or his
close supporters be included in an interim civilian government.
</P>
<P>
"We have stated this is impossible," Bainimarama said.
</P>
<P>
"We would like them to leave, have the hostages released and
return all arms so we can bring some normalcy back to our lives,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Bainimarama did not say what would happen if Speight ignored
the ultimatum.
</P>
<P>
But military spokesman Filipo Tarakinikini said talks had
reached a "critical and volatile point."
</P>
<P>
He said no further negotiations were scheduled on Monday with
Speight, but added: "We are still leaving the door open for talks.
"
</P>
<P>
Bainimarama said foreign governments had warned of a major
economic backlash against Fiji if the military agreed to Speight's
demands.
</P>
<P>
The European Union had written to Fiji warning that if Speight
was included in a new government it would not buy Fiji sugar, one
of the Pacific nation's most valuable exports.
</P>
<P>
Bainimarama also said the concerns of Speight and other
indigenous Fijians would be reflected in a new constitution.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the hostages being held in the parliament complex
are well, medical and diplomatic sources said.
</P>
<P>
Speight Sunday night would not say when he would release them,
again declaring they were his trump cards in any negotiations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000605.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Deeply Concerned by Solomon Islands Coup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Australia was deeply concerned by
an apparent coup in the Solomon Islands, Foreign Minister
Alexander Downer said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Downer said Solomons Prime Minister Bartholomew Ulufa'alu had
been taken at gunpoint by rebels but was now safe and no longer in
detention.
</P>
<P>
"We are obviously very deeply concerned about what has taken
place during the course of last night," Downer told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"We understand that the governor-general and the prime minister
are both safe," he said.
</P>
<P>
"This has happened after we have made a very substantial effort
to try to stabilize the situation in the Solomon Islands and we
will be continuing to do that," he said.
</P>
<P>
Downer said he understood that no hostages were being held by
the Malaita Eagle Force rebels.
</P>
<P>
"The information that I have now is that the prime minister is
able to move freely around as is the governor-general although
they do have Malaita Eagle Force people with them," he said.
</P>
<P>
"But they are not being confined to any one particular location
or held hostage," he said.
</P>
<P>
"But the leader of the Malaita Eagle Force, Andrew Nori, is
simply insisting that the prime minister resign," Downer said.
</P>
<P>
Downer said it was too early to make any judgments about what
would happen.
</P>
<P>
"The prime minister himself has offered to resign last weekend
so what his political fate will be now, we don't exactly know and
that remains to be seen during the course of, presumably, today or
tomorrow," Downer said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
