<HEADLINE> Jakarta to Hold Miss Indonesia Contest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The Miss Indonesia beauty contest
is to be held here this week after a four-year gap, according to
chairwoman of the Miss Indonesia Foundation Mooryati Soedibyo.
</P>
<P>
She said the fifth contest, from June 7 to 10, would be
attended by 30 girls from 25 of the country's 26 provinces and the
newly elected Miss Universe 2000 from India Lara Dutta is expected
to join in.
</P>
<P>
"The contestants will be judged based on their intellectual
ability, behavior and beauty," Mooryati was quoted by the Jakarta
Post Monday as saying.
</P>
<P>
The grand finale of the beauty contest would be held next
Saturday at the Taman Mini Indonesia Indah (Beautiful Indonesia in
Miniature Park) and be attended by some 1,000 people, said
Mooryati, a businesswoman who runs a cosmetics company.
</P>
<P>
State Minister for Women's Empowerment Khofifah Indar Parawansa
said the government supported the event.
</P>
<P>
She said contests such as these should view women an asset, not
a commodity to be exploited. The minister also said the urine of
each candidate would be checked to make sure that she was not a
drug user.
</P>
<P>
Minister for Tourism and the Arts Hidayat Jaelani said he hoped
the event would help restore the country's image, which had been
badly tarnished by social unrest and political uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
He said the winner of Miss Indonesia would represent the
country as a tourist ambassador at international events.
</P>
<P>
Beauty contests were banned by the government of former
president Soeharto on the grounds that they treated women as
objects and were against religious and Eastern values in general.
</P>
</TEXT>
