<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Sino-Myanmar Friendly Ties Grow Steadily By Duan Tingchang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar, which established
diplomatic relations with China on June 8, 1950, was among the
first countries which made the move.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 50 years, bilateral relations between the two
countries have stood the test of the changing international
political climate, growing steadily.
</P>
<P>
China and Myanmar share identical or similar views on many
major international issues, supporting each other and cooperating
closely in international affairs.
</P>
<P>
The mutual trust and support politically have become an
important cornerstone for the development of friendly and
cooperative ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
In the past 50 years, Myanmar has consistently supported China'
s solemn stand in safeguarding its state sovereignty and
territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar recognizes that the government of the People's Republic
of China is the sole legitimate government representing the whole
of China and that Taiwan is an inalienable part of China's
territory.
</P>
<P>
The frequent exchanges of visits by leaders of China and
Myanmar have signified the steady development of the two countries
' bilateral ties. These visits have pushed ahead the smooth
development of the two countries' political and economic ties.
</P>
<P>
In bilateral cooperation in the sectors of economy and
technology, remarkable progress has been made.
</P>
<P>
Since the establishment of diplomatic relations, China and
Myanmar have signed three agreements on economic and technical
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
China has carried out dozens of construction projects in
Myanmar. These include a sugar mill, a paper mill, a textile mill,
a plywood factory, a ball factory, a thermal power plant, a rice
mill, a national theater, a national stadium, and the Yangon-
Thanlyin highway and railway combined bridge. The projects are
playing an important role in Myanmar's economic development.
</P>
<P>
In addition to economic assistance, the two countries have also
launched other forms of economic cooperation. Chinese companies
have initiated a number of contracted projects in Myanmar, with
some in the form of wholly Chinese investment or joint venture.
More than 10 Chinese enterprises have already been set up in
Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
In the trade sector, Myanmar is one of the main importing
countries of China's consumer goods and electrical household
appliances. China is now Myanmar's second largest trading partner
with annual bilateral trade amounting to about 600 million U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Border trade is an important supplement to China-Myanmar
bilateral trade. The two countries have opened on their respective
sides nine border trade points, greatly enhancing bilateral trade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000605.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shooting Continues in Aceh, Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Two people were shot and injured in
Indonesia's restive province of Aceh on Sunday despite the fact a
cease-fire between the Indonesian Military (TNI) and the Free Aceh
Movement (GAM) had taken effect two days earlier, press reports
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Local police were investigating the shooting, reports reaching
Monday from Aceh said.
</P>
<P>
The reports said that some 100 houses under construction for
local transmigrants were also burned down by unknown people at
Abah Lueng village in Bandar Baru sub-district, Pidie regency.
</P>
<P>
A historic cease-fire came into effect Friday throughout Aceh
after 25 years of violence during which more than 5,000 people
have died.
</P>
<P>
Last year at least 250 houses for transmigrants were also set
on fire at Geumpang Sub-district, Pidie regency.
</P>
<P>
Rebels in Aceh, a province with the special autonomous status
in northwestern Sumatra, have been fighting for 25 years for
independence, a greater share of oil profits, and the right to
impose Islamic religious laws.
</P>
<P>
At least 399 people have died this year, 30 of them soldiers or
policemen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
