<HEADLINE> Solomon Islands' Labor Leader: PM Held Captive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Solomon Islands' Labor Party
leader said the country's prime minister has been held captive
since 6:00 a.m. (local time) Monday as part of a coup unfolding in
the capital Honiara, the Australian Broadcasting Corporation (ABC)
reported.
</P>
<P>
The ABC quoted Joses Tuhanuku, a former Solomon Islands' MP who
is presently in Canberra, as saying he was in contact with
colleagues in Honiara before phone lines were cut off.
</P>
<P>
He said the coup was sparked by similar events in Fiji and he
has been told a group calling themselves the Malaita Eagle Force
is responsible.
</P>
<P>
"There are two ethnic groups that have been in conflict over
land issues and it's not very clear yet over what the demands are
and who may be really responsible, but the little bit I heard from
home is that the prime minister has been held since 6:00 a.m.," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The office of Australian Foreign Minister Alexander Downer said
Australia has been in contact with sources from the Solomon
Islands' government.
</P>
<P>
Downer is expected to make a more detailed statement later
Monday. 
