<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Gorges Project Does not Affect River Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The construction of the Three
Gorges project has not affected the quality of water of the
Yangtze River, according to a release here today.
</P>
<P>
The release by the State Environmental Protection
Administration of China (SEPA) said the quality in the trunk river
of the Yangtze remains good, or up to level II or III despite
large-scale building of the dam area near Yichang city of Hubei
Province, central China.
</P>
<P>
"The Bulletin on the Ecology and Environment in the Three
Gorges Area of the Yangtze River in 1999", jointly compiled by the
SEPA and nine other government departments and research groups,
said progress was reported in urban waste water treatment, and
garbage disposal and discharge of pollutants into the river and
its tributaries have decreased.
</P>
<P>
White-flag dolphins, Chinese sturgeons and other endangered
species have been well protected, it added.
</P>
<P>
Yet, the bulletin pointed out, environmental problems remain in
the future reservoir region with a population of nearly 20 million,
such as rural energy shortage, continuing decrease of fuel forest
and serious loss of water and soil.
</P>
<P>
Random dumping of garbage into the river by ships and
landslides and other geological accidents are not rare and the
construction of urban waste water and garbage treatment facilities
is going very slow, said the 44-page bulletin in eight chapters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
