<DOCNO> XIE20000605.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Govt to Take Stern Actions Against Separatist Activities in Irian Jaya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Abdurrahman
Wahid and Indonesian Military (TNI) chief Widodo have pledged to
take stern measures against the Papuans (Irian Jaya) for declaring
independence, House of Representatives Speaker Akbar Tanjung said.
</P>
<P>
The House would support every means sought by the government to
maintain the state's unity, Akbar said on Sunday in Pangkalpinang,
South Sumatra province.
</P>
<P>
"I have phoned Wahid and asked him not to hesitate in taking
strict action to keep the country's territorial integrity,"
reports reaching here Monday quoted the House speaker as saying.
</P>
<P>
"I also have phoned TNI chief Widodo to discuss the same thing
I did with President Wahid," Akbar added.
</P>
<P>
The week-long "Papua National Congress" ended on Sunday in
Jayapura, capital of Papua province, with the adoption of a
resolution declaring Papua's incorporation into Indonesia in the
1960s invalid and stating that the resource-rich province is an
independence state.
</P>
<P>
Pro-independence leader Theys Eluay told the congress that
Papua would aim to seek independence through negotiations and
peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
The House speaker added that President Wahid has ordered the
TNI chief to take effective steps to prevent such a movement from
leading to separatism.
</P>
<P>
He also said that Wahid has summoned the ambassadors of Britain,
the United States, the Netherlands and Australia to explain their
governments' stance in dealing with the Papua problem.
</P>
<P>
Australia and the Netherlands have stated their support for
Indonesia's national integrity, said Akbar.
</P>
<P>
Wahid said over the weekend that most people in the province
want to remain part of Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Papua (Irian Jaya) is the largest island in Indonesia with a
population of about two million.
</P>
<P>
In 1963, then president Sukarno led Indonesia's fight to regain
the mineral-rich territory from the Netherlands. It was officially
integrated into Indonesia after a U.N.-sponsored plebiscite in
1969. 
</P>
</TEXT>
