<HEADLINE> 1stlead: Australia Confirms Groups Overrun Installations in Honiara  (Adds statement, closure of Solomon airport) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Australia's Department of Foreign
Affairs and Trade Monday morning confirmed armed groups had
overrun key installations in Honiara, capital of the Solomon
Islands overnight, in an apparent coup attempt.
</P>
<P>
"Members of the Malaita Eagle Force rebel group have taken over
key installations in Honiara including some police stations and
the Government Telecommunications Center," the department said in
a statement.
</P>
<P>
"Armed rebels have taken control of major intersections in
Honiara," the department said.
</P>
<P>
"These actions represent a significant deterioration in the
tensions between ethnic groups reported in previous travel
advisories," the department said.
</P>
<P>
Australians have been warned to defer travel to the South
Pacific nation.
</P>
<P>
Australians currently in Honiara should stay indoors, exercise
a high level of personal security awareness and await further
advice, the department said.
</P>
<P>
But the department could not confirm a report that the rebels
had taken Prime Minister Bartholomew Ulufa'alu hostage.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Australian Foreign Minister Alexander Downer
said information was still being sought by the government.
</P>
<P>
Downer could make a statement later Monday, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Associated Press (AAP) quoted Solomon Islands
civil aviation department sources as saying that an attempted coup
is underway with a rebel militia group placing the prime minister
under house arrest.
</P>
<P>
Telephone lines to the island nation have been cut and the
airport closed, the civil aviation department was quoted by the
AAP as saying.
</P>
<P>
The department's flight operations center at Honiara airport
said the rebels had raided a police armory and were in control of
the streets of the capital.
</P>
<P>
"All flights in and out of Honiara have been suspended until
further notice...this includes domestic operations," the
department said.
</P>
<P>
The Malaita Eagles are one of two rival groups who have been
fighting for more than 18 months.
</P>
<P>
About 60 people have been killed in the fighting. The other
group is known as the Istabu Revolutionary Front. 
</P>
