<HEADLINE> Berlin Introduces First Car-Free Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Germany's capital city of Berlin had
its first car-free day Sunday by banning private cars from its
streets to improve air quality and reduce traffic congestion and
noise pollution.
</P>
<P>
Berlin residents were encouraged to take buses and streetcars,
or ride bicycles or go on roller-skates. Those using public
transportation systems only needed to pay an average of 3.9 German
marks for a daily ticket, which was equivalent to half of the
normal price.
</P>
<P>
A total of 30,000 people, including many federal and city
parliament members, took part in Sunday's bicycle-riding organized
by the German Bicycle Club, police said. They started from 13
different sites in the suburban areas and converged on the
Brandenburger Tor Gate in the city center.
</P>
<P>
A new traffic rule will be worked out to encourage Berliners to
ride bicycles, said Peter Strieder, Berlin's environment
commissioner, who also participated in Sunday's bicycle-riding.
</P>
</TEXT>
