<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Military in Charge of Fiji: TV Reports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The Fijian military said on Monday
it was firmly in charge of Fiji while continuing to negotiate with
coup leader George Speight, Australia's Nine TV Network reported.
</P>
<P>
When asked who was running Fiji, a military spokesman confirmed
the military was in control.
</P>
<P>
Fijian military spokesman Lieutenant Colonel Filipo
Tarakinikini told the network's Today show that the military line
had been drawn and Speight must agree to their demands.
</P>
<P>
"The military line has been drawn and we have told Mr. Speight
and his group that beyond this we are not going to negotiate," the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"The hostages should be returned, weapons, ammunition returned
and the military bring back normalcy back to the whole country,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"And this can last maybe up to three months at the most and
then we will divert back to the Great Council of Chiefs and from
then on an interim civilian administration," he added.
</P>
<P>
Surrender of any weapons in the parliamentary complex was now a
prerequisite, he said.
</P>
<P>
Speight Sunday night again refused to say when he would release
his hostages, but said talks with Fiji's interim military
government aimed at freeing the captives and deciding Fiji's
political future were going well.
</P>
<P>
The Great Council of Chiefs will be asked to decide whether to
back continued military rule or a Speight-aligned civilian
government.
</P>
<P>
Since Speight seized parliament, Fiji's elected government and
its president have been removed, its constitution revoked and
military rule enforced. 
</P>
</TEXT>
