<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Ends Work to Set Line to Verify Israeli Pullout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 5 (Xinhua) -- U.N. special envoy Terje Roed-Larsen
announced here Monday night that U.N. cartographers have confirmed
the line that will be used to verify Israel's withdrawal form south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Larsen told reporters following his talks with Lebanese leaders
that the U.N. team has wrapped up setting the line between Israel
and Lebanon. "The U.N. will verify whether Israel's withdrawal from
south Lebanon is complete or not according to the line," Larsen
added.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.N. experts will end their work on some concerning
part along the line.
</P>
<P>
Larsen will meet Lebanese President Emile Lahoud and Prime
Minister Salim Hoss Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
He did not mention three areas along the Israeli-Lebanese
border, which are under Israeli control but claimed by Lebanon.
Neither did he talk about the disputed Shebaa Farms over which
Beirut says it has ownership.
</P>
<P>
The 200-square kilometer, fertile Shebaa area is located on the
west side of Mount Hermon, which is under Israeli occupation.
Israel argues that the Shebaa Farms belong to Syria, and that a
withdrawal from the area would be considered in peace talks with
Damascus when they resume.
</P>
<P>
Local radio quoted a government source as saying that Beirut has
agreed to deal with this issue in separate fashion after Larsen's
visit to Syria and his talks with Foreign Minister Faruk Shareh.
</P>
<P>
Syria is the main power broker in Lebanon. Its peace
negotiations with Israel has been stalled in February due to
Israel's refusal to promise the full return of the Golan Heights it
captured in 1967 Middle East war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000605.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Halts Negotiations with Shas over Funding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
ordered Monday to stop the negotiations with the ultra-Orthodox
Jewish Shas Party over its demands for more government money for
its financially ailing educational network.
</P>
<P>
The move came in response to threats by the powerful religious
party to support Knesset (Parliament) member Avigdor Liberman's
bill proposal for early elections, which will be brought to a vote
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We will not act under threats," Barak said.
</P>
<P>
Shas party, which holds 17 seats in the 120-member Knesset, has
been in a long-time feud with the left-wing Meretz Party over
funding and control of the Shas religious school system, the power
base of the relatively young political force that has grown up
suddenly in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The wrangling between Shas, the third largest party after Labor
and Likud in the ruling coalition, and the fourth-largest party
Meretz, has touched off a 10-month-long coalition crisis which
rattled Barak's fragile coalition government.
</P>
<P>
Shas had blamed Education Minister Yossi Sarid of the Meretz
Party for refusing to allocate enough funds to cover Shas'
financial deficits in its ailing educational system, while Sarid
argued that the system management was corrupt and should be
reformed first. 
</P>
<P>
The disputes were resolved temporarily before last December's
state budget vote after the two sides signed a restructuring deal
regarding the issue.
</P>
<P>
Later, Shas again updated its demand list by urging Sarid to
hand over the control of the ultra-Orthodox school system to his
deputy Meshulam Nahari, who is a Shas member.
</P>
<P>
Sarid, vehemently opposed to reopening the deal, has warned that
his party could bolt the government if Barak orders him to open
Education Ministry coffers further for Shas schools.
</P>
<P>
Barak has been working hard but in vain to forge compromise
proposals to end the crisis between the two irreconcilable ruling
partners, both of which are pivotal for the stability of the ruling
coalition.
</P>
<P>
Barak, who holds a 68-52 seat majority in the parliament, is now
engaged in talks with U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright,
who arrived here on Monday to boost the lagging Israeli-Palestinian
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The impact of his decision to halt the negotiations with Shas on
the ruling coalition and further on the peace process remains to be
seen.
</P>
<P>
Labor and Social Affairs Minister Eli Yishai, the Shas leader,
congratulated Barak on his decision by saying that "The prime
minister has finally understood that the 10-month talks have
brought no results, and it is time for the prime minister to make
the final decision." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000605.0307 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
