<HEADLINE> Iranian Envoy Underlines Anti-Terrorism Stance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Deputy Foreign Minister
Mohammad Hossein Adeli on Monday rebuffed allegations that Tehran
wants to destabilize Turkey through a series of political killings,
reported Turkey's Anatolia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Adeli, who came to Turkey to invite Turkish President Ahmet
Necdet
Sezer to attend the Economic Cooperation Organization (ECO) summit
to be held in Tehran on June 10, told reporters that it was simply
not in the Iranian interests to have relations with Turkey
overshadowed by terrorism.
</P>
<P>
He expressed Iran's disappointment at the press reports
vilifying
Iran for destabilizing Turkey, adding that the two countries should
make utmost efforts to keep calm while dealing with temporary
problems.
</P>
<P>
Iran has been the target of growing criticism in recent weeks
after Turkish police leaked stories that several leading Turkish
intellectuals were assassinated by Iranian agents in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
However, it turned out later that the accusations against Iran
were overplayed in the press.
</P>
<P>
In view of the new development, it was reported, Prime Minister
Bulent Ecevit and Foreign Minister Ismail Cem last Tuesday advised
the newly-elected president to attend the ECO summit which will
also be attended by important leaders from Central Asia.
</P>
<P>
During his brief stay in Ankara, Adeli met Foreign Ministry
Deputy Undersecretary Mithat Balkan, mainly discussing his mission
in the capacity of a special envoy to convey Khatami's invitation
to Sezer.
</P>
<P>
Underscoring the significance of the Iranian president's
message, the emissary noted that confidence should be built up
among different cultures and people of the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
