<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FCC Gives Conditional Approval to AT&AMP;T's Purchase of MediaOne </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 5 (Xinhua) -- U.S. federal regulators on
Monday gave conditional clearance to AT&AMP;T Corp.'s proposed
purchase of MediaOne, a deal that makes the nation's top long-
distance carrier also the top cable company.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Communications Commission (FCC) conditioned its
approval on AT&AMP;T shedding some assets so that it would comply with
federal rules that limit how many customers a single cable company
can reach. AT&AMP;T has one year to complete the necessary divesture.
</P>
<P>
FCC approval is the final regulatory hurdle. Two weeks ago, The
Justice Department had signed off on the deal, originally valued
at 58 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The merger will further AT&AMP;T's plan to offer high-speed
Internet access, local phone service and television programming
directly into homes using cable TV lines. That allows them to
bypass the phone networks owned by the Bell companies to bring
these services to consumers.
</P>
<P>
Under the commission's action, AT&AMP;T has three options for
coming under the federal ownership limits. It can get rid of
MediaOne's 25 percent interest in cable systems owned by Time
Warner, it could shed programming interests that sell to Time
Warner's cable system, or it could get rid of more than 9.7
million of its cable subscribers.
</P>
<P>
FCC rules forbid one company from controlling more than 30
percent of the multichannel video market, which includes cable and
competitors such as direct broadcast satellite. The limits are
meant to ensure that consumers have a diversity of content
available to them.
</P>
<P>
FCC Chairman William Kennard said the commission action would
promote competition in the local phone markets while protecting
consumer interests in high-speed Internet service and cable TV
programming. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000605.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudan Urges Lifting of Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Sudan Monday urged the
United Nations Security Council to lift the sanctions which have
been in place since 1996.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the president of the United Nations Security
Council, Sudanese Foreign Minister Mustafa Osman Ismail said his
country had made sincere and pragmatic efforts to comply with the
demands made upon it.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said inquiries in the past years had shown
that no trace was found of the three suspects in the Sudan, who
are accused for the 1995 assassination attempt against Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak in Addis Ababa.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister listed a series of steps that Sudan had
taken since the United Nations Security Council called on it to
desist from engaging in terrorist activities and to improve its
relations with its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Ismail urged the president of the Security Council to convene a
special meeting in order to lift the sanctions imposed on the
country in the light of the practical and concrete measures that
the Sudanese government has taken to meet the Council's demands.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions, imposed in May 1996, require all states to
reduce the number of Sudanese diplomatic personnel on their
territory and to restrict the entry or transit of Sudanese
governmental officials.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council also decided in August 1996 to impose
sanctions against flights by Sudanese aircraft. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000605.0311 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Textiles and Garment Trade Show Opens in United States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 5 (Xinhua) -- A China Textiles and Garment Trade
Show opened here Monday in what is the first Chinese professional
textiles and garment fair in the United States.
</P>
<P>
The event, "Year 2000 China Textiles and Garment Trade Show,"
attracted some 206 enterprises from 25 Chinese provinces and
cities in an exhibition area of 5,000 square meters.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony, Wang Tiankai, deputy
director of the China Textile and Industrial Bureau, said, "China
and the United States are key trading partners. The two countries
are highly complementary to each other in the economic field."
</P>
<P>
"This expo is mainly designed for the better understanding on
the American market for Chinese textiles and garment enterprises
in a more direct way so as to provide better services in trade
exchanges," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Meanwhile, through widespread contact with American
enterprises, they can seek opportunities for cooperation on
capital, technology and other means from American enterprises, so
that the trade and commerce of two countries would be expanded and
the economic growth of the two countries be benefited," he said.
</P>
<P>
"With fast development of worldwide science and technology,
and the further progress of the economic globalization, the Sino-
American connections in economy, technology and trade should not
only be further strengthened, but also be promoted to maturity,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Li Zhaoxing, Chinese ambassador to the United States,
Ambassador Shen Guofang, deputy Chinese representative to the
United Nations, and Ambassador Zhang Hongxi, Chinese consul
general in New York, were present at the opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Organized by the China's Sub-Council of Textile Industry and
the China Council for the Promotion of International Trade, the
show will end Wednesday. It was supported by the U.S. Specialty
Trade Shows and the Fully Youthful Enterprise.
</P>
<P>
Textile industry is a major pillar of China's national economy,
and China's textile industry has kept vigorous vitality thanks to
the nation's reform and opening to the outside world campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
