<HEADLINE> N.Irish Assembly Holds First Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The order of business on Monday included a motion by the
Democratic Unionist Party (DUP) that the Union Flag should fly
from government buildings on designated days.
</P>
<P>
The party has tabled a motion to compel Sinn Fein ministers,
Martin McGuinness and Bairbre de Brun to fly the Union Flag from
their departmental headquarters on those days.
</P>
<P>
McGuinness, who is Northern Ireland's education minister, and
Ms. De Brun, who is health minister, angered unionists on Friday
by ordering their civil servants not to fly the flag which was
part of the celebration of the anniversary of Queen Elizabeth's
coronation.
</P>
<P>
The DUP leader, Ian Paisley, who has tabled the motion with
party colleague and social development minister Nigel Dodds,
branded Sinn Fein's actions "a disgrace".
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein President Gerry Adams said in Belfast that the first
meeting of the assembly marked "another effort to make these
institutions work". "There has been three months lost in which a
lot of valuable work could have been done," he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Deputy First Minister Seamus Mallon said he believed
the flags issue could be resolved.
</P>
<P>
Britain boosted the flagging peace process last week by
restoring home-rule powers to the assembly and a 12-member cabinet,
which it suspended in February over the Irish Republican Army's (
IRA) failure to disarm. 
</P>
</TEXT>
