<HEADLINE> Eurostar Bullet Train Derails in Northern France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 5 (Xinhua) -- A Eurostar bullet train running at
300 kilometers per hour from Paris to London derailed Monday
afternoon near Arras in Pas-de-Calais, northern France, said
French officials.
</P>
<P>
Thirteen people were slightly injured in the accident, which
took place at 17:45 local time (15:5 GMT), said the French state
railway company SNCF.
</P>
<P>
Only two bogies went out of the rails while the whole body of
the train, which had 501 passengers on board, remained on the
track, said SNCF.
</P>
<P>
After the accident took place, SNCF shifted all the other
Eurostar trains to the classic tracks going through the English
channel and the passengers of the derailed train were transported
by bus to the nearby city of Lille, where they took a special
train for Britain.
</P>
<P>
French officials said that the cause of the accident has not
been found and Minister of Transport Jean-Claude Gayssot has
ordered all the personnel of SNCF to stay vigilant to meet "extra
requests of security in railway operation."
</P>
<P>
The derailment of the Eurostar took place one day after a
railway was sabotaged in Isere, southeast France, by an Algerian
man who was said to be mentally ill.
</P>
<P>
The sabotage caused the derailment of an international train
from Vintimille, Italy, to Calais, northern France, killing two
people and injuring a dozen others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
