<HEADLINE> Colombia, Venezuela Trade Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Trade between Colombia and Venezuela
grew 29 percent in this year's first quarter, showing a vigorous
recovery following a severe fall in 1999, Venezuela's ambassador
Fernando Gerbassi said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Colombia's exports to Venezuela went up from January to March
by 42 percent over last year's same period, and inversely 16
percent, said Gerbassi, in statements made known Monday by the
local RCN radio station.
</P>
<P>
"This is an indication of a recovery, though still slow, that
is coming about in both countries' economies," said this official,
when recalling that the year before recession affected both
Colombia and Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
He added in Caracas that foreign and trade ministers and
entrepreneurs from both countries evaluated at a meeting the
course of commerce and adopted new measures to recover bilateral
exchange dynamism.
</P>
<P>
"The Caracas meeting is a development of accords that arrived
at a conference of President Andres Pastrana (of Colombia) and
President Hugo Chavez (of Venezuela) in Santa Marta de Colombia
last month," the ambassador explained. 
</P>
</TEXT>
