<HEADLINE> Canada to Negotiate Free Trade Agreement with Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Canada and Singapore will begin
exploring the possibility of negotiating a bilateral free trade
agreement, the Canadian government announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
Canadian International Trade Minister Pierre Pettigrew has met
with Singaporean Trade and Industry Minister George Yeo "on the
margins of the Meeting of APEC Ministers Responsible for Trade" in
Darwin, Australia, the government announcement said.
</P>
<P>
This would be another deal to facilitate trade for Canada,
which has free trade agreements in place with the United States
and Mexico through the North American Free Trade Agreement, as
well as bilateral agreements with Chile and Israel.
</P>
<P>
The country is also pursuing a free trade deal with the
European Free Trade Association.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, Canada exported 367 million Canadian dollars (about
249 million U.S. dollars) in goods to Singapore and imported about
1.2 billion (about 814 million U.S. dollars), said the government
announcement.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Canada invested about 2.4 billion Canadian dollars (
about 1.6 billion U.S. dollars) in Singapore, whose direct
investment into Canadian businesses totaled about 152 million (
about 103 million U.S. dollars) at the same time, said the
announcement.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian government described the agri-food, aerospace,
defense, life sciences, construction and environment industries as
key sectors emerging as opportunities for Canadian business in
Singapore. 
</P>
</TEXT>
