<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Ministers Sign Statement in Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Health ministers of World
Health Organization (WHO) countries signed Monday in Mexico's
capital the Mexico Declaration for promoting world health
development.
</P>
<P>
Ministers signed this declaration during the inaugural ceremony
of the 5th World Conference of Health Promotion Mexico-2000, that
will take place from June 5 to 9 in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
Attending the ceremony as witnesses were Mexico's President
Ernesto Zedillo, WHO General Director Harlem Brundtland, and Pan-
American Health Organization (PHO) Director George A.O. Alleyne.
</P>
<P>
In the joint statement the participating ministers concluded
that health promotion must be a fundamental part of health
policies and programs in all countries in the search for fairness
and better health for all.
</P>
<P>
They considered that the promotion of sanitary and health
development is a top priority, as well as a governmental
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
Top officials from around 100 delegations in the world agreed
it is urgent to cover health's social, economic and environmental
determinants and that this requires reinforced collaboration
mechanisms to promote health in every sector and all society
levels.
</P>
<P>
This statement called upon United Nations organizations to be
responsible for effects upon health of their development programs
and that member countries inform WHO of progresses made in
carrying out actions mentioned above.
</P>
<P>
Previous four conferences of this kind took place at Ottawa,
Canada, in 1986; Adeleide, Australia, in 1988; Sundswall, Sweden,
in 1991; and Jakarta, Indonesia, in 1997, respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
