<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets Run Out Of Steam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Europe's leading stock markets ended
lower Monday as a technology, telecom and media stock rally of
last week appeared to run out of steam.
</P>
<P>
London's benchmark FTSE 100 index led the way lower, falling 79.
7 points, or 1.2 percent to 6,546.7, after rising nearly 7 percent
last week and hitting a 9-week high Friday.
</P>
<P>
Two would-be merger partners in the pharmaceuticals sector led
the market's losers. Glaxo Wellcome fell 5.9 percent and its
partner SmithKline Beecham dropped 5.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the "new economy" sector, Internet service provider
Freeserve fell 5.7 percent, broadcaster BSKyB dropped 5.6 percent
and telecom operator Cable &AMP; Wireless fell 3.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
German shares ended slightly lower after last week's rally but
still searched for direction in line with other European markets.
</P>
<P>
Deutsche Telekom was among the biggest losers, off 2 percent,
while electronics and engineering company Siemens fell 1.5 percent,
although both pared their early losses.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, the CAC 40 index fell 17.26 points, or 0.3 percent,
to 6,654.96, after closing at a record high Friday and climbing 9
percent for the week as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Shares of pay-TV company Canal Plus fell 4 percent, rival
broadcaster TF1 shed 2.6 percent and defense-and-media firm
Lagardere dropped 3 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
