<HEADLINE> Tanzania, Rwanda Agree to Maintain Regional Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian and Rwandan defense
 ministers agreed here on Monday to collaborate in attaining peace
in the Great Lakes region to benefit economic activities.
</P>
<P>
After a meeting held in the Defense Ministry, Tanzanian
Minister of Defense Maokola Majogo and his visiting Rwandan
counterpart Emmanual Habyarimana said that they want to foster a
friendly bilateral relationship on defense and security matters.
</P>
<P>
"If there is peace and security within the area, people will
live in peace and economic development activities will take place
without hindrance, " Majogo told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the importance of regular meetings of the two
country's defense ministers and their chief of defense forces on
security matters as well as exchange of officers for training.
</P>
<P>
Habyarimana said that he expected to learn more from Tanzania
experience on matters of defense and security.
</P>
<P>
He also talked about the situation in Kisangani in the eastern
part of the Democratic Republic of the Congo and denied claims
that there are Rwandan troops stationed in neighboring Burundi.
</P>
<P>
The visit of Habyarimana, who was accompanied by Rwandan Chief
of Security Lieutenant Colonel Patrick Kalegeya and other
officers, is seen as another positive development in the peace
efforts in the region following a summit between presidents
Laurent Kabila of the DRC and Paul Kagame of Rwanda over the
weekend in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents, at the invitation of Kenyan President
Daniel arap Moi, met in Eldoret town and resolved to work together
to promote peace, security and stability in both countries and the
Great Lakes region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
