<HEADLINE> Ugandan Army Vehicle Ambushed in Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- A vehicle belonging to the Uganda
People's Defense Forces (UPDF) was ambushed and burnt Monday
morning in Kisangani, a northeast city of the Democratic Republic
of the Congo.
</P>
<P>
The vehicle was ambushed at a T-junction at Kabondo on its way
back from a mission of sending logistics to UPDF members at the
Bangoka Airport, said a press release signed by State Minister for
Defense Steven Kavuma.
</P>
<P>
The UPDF vehicle, which was escorted by a vehicle of the United
Nations Observer Mission in Congo (MONUC), was attacked by small
arms at first and then by rocket-propelled grenades which
destroyed it, the release said, adding that the MONUC vehicle
drove through the ambush successfully.
</P>
<P>
Later there was firing directed to Kapalata, a UPDF position
across the Tshopo River, compelling UPDF to respond, the release
said, stressing that the UPDF shelling was aimed at positions
where the original shelling started.
</P>
<P>
Kavuma could not readily confirm who attacked the UPDF vehicle
but he said it must have been forces not very much amused by
demilitarization of Kisangani.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, the demilitarization of Kisangani
appeared to proceed successfully through the first phase which
ended last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
UPDF remains committed to the demilitarization of Kisangani and
the total observance of all the provisions of the Lusaka
cease-fire agreement, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
