<HEADLINE> Mandela to Meet Burundian President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Nelson Mandela, former South
African president and now chief mediator for Burundi's peace
process, is to meet Burundian President Pierre Buyoya and Defense
Minister Cyrille Ndayirukiye here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The talks come ahead of a planned visit by Mandela to Burundi
later this month to meet with armed groups and people in the
country's controversial regroupment camps, reported South African
Press Association on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Mandela's office declined to elaborate on the talks with Buyoya
and Ndayirukiye, only saying they are part of the ongoing peace
process.
</P>
<P>
However, Mandela himself said earlier this month that he would
demand Bujumbura to lift the restrictions imposed on the political
opposition parties and the media in the war-torn African country.
</P>
<P>
The 81-year-old statesman last month held separate closed-door
discussions with rebel groups and Burundi government
representatives to woo their support for his peace initiative.
</P>
<P>
The Burundi peace process has dragged on for two years, with
violence continuing on the ground, but Mandela is now trying to
force the pace by drawing up a series of compromise proposals
based on the negotiations, hoping for an agreement in July.
</P>
<P>
War broke out in Burundi in 1993, pitting several rebel Hutu
factions against the Tutsi-dominated government and army.
</P>
<P>
Hutus represent 85 percent of Burundi's population, but are
mostly peasants and farmers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
