<DOCNO> XIE20000605.0330 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africans Urged to Manage Waste Well </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Plastic bags are only the tip
of the iceberg of South Africa's waste management problem, said
Environment Minister Valli Moosa at a World Environment Day event
in Cape Town on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Although these are the most visible problem, they are not the
only one, he told an audience that included school children and
models dressed in recycled plastic fashions.
</P>
<P>
The big problem is the way South Africa mismanaged its waste
and the " don't care attitude" of consumers who simply tossed
their waste out of their yard or dumped it on street corners, he
said, noting that this attitude will take a long time to overcome.
</P>
<P>
Comparing to the fact that Denmark recycles up to 95 percent of
its waste annually, the figure for South Africa is only 3 or 4
percent and the remaining 96 percent goes into landfill sites, or
can be found in rivers, streams, wetlands "and generally lying
around all over the show", the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Moosa, who last month published draft regulations to outlaw
conventional thin plastic shopping bags, said he does not intend
to rush in an authoritarian way with legislation to ban plastic
bags completely or to set up a "plastic bag unit" in the police.
</P>
<P>
He said he would like to give adequate opportunity for changes
to happen through the development of a social conscience.
</P>
<P>
An African renaissance or rebirth could only happen if it is
associated with citizens' sense of pride in themselves and in
their surroundings, Moosa said, warning that "you will never have
a sense of pride if you live in filth all around you." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
