<HEADLINE> Ecuador's Central Bank Destroys Half of Circulating Sucre </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Ecuador's Central Bank has up to now
destroyed 6 billion sucre bills, half of the country's circulating
currency amount.
</P>
<P>
Director of this institute's Money House Carlos Villagomez said
Monday at a press conference that since February, after the "
dollarization" adoption, half of the national currency cash has
been destroyed, especially 50,000 sucre bills which were
substituted by dollars imported from the United States.
</P>
<P>
Up to the coming September, sucres and dollars will keep
circulating in parallel, said Villagomez. He also said that the
Central Bank foresees importing 8 million dollars in currency
fractions to cover the lack of "small currency."
</P>
<P>
Ecuador decided to eliminate its currency and adopt the dollar
as exchange means, although the sucre will keep circulating for
three months more as American coin fraction.
</P>
<P>
"Dollarization" has been applied with a fixed exchange of 25,000
sucres per dollar, which has generated confusion among the
population for calculating fractions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
