<HEADLINE> Mexico Rejects Fear of Criticism Regarding Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Mexican Foreign Secretary
Rosario Green said Monday that facing the coming July 2 elections
in her country, Mexico's government is passing through similar
criticisms to those Peru experiences nowadays.
</P>
<P>
"Mexico is open to criticism and election observation," and
therefore there will be thousands of observers, Green said in
Windsor, Canada, where she attends the 30th General Assembly of
the Organization of American States (OAS), according to reports
reaching here.
</P>
<P>
Mexico's diplomatic head told the press that her country is
opposed to every condemnation of or sanction on Peru and holds
that the OAS lacks power to impose punishment to any member
country of this international organization.
</P>
<P>
The OAS' observation mission considered illegitimate the
triumph of Peruvian leader Alberto Fujimori in the May 28
elections, owing to withdrawal of opposer Alejandro Toledo, and
therefore this country's election authorities are trying to
legitimize this process.
</P>
<P>
Green said, "Mexico's stance is that we don't discuss Peru's
elections (at the assembly), but rather on the principle what
interests Peruvians (have) in a cooperation program between the
OAS and their government to strengthen democratic institutions."
</P>
<P>
Mexico will hold on July 2 general elections in which millions
of Mexicans will go to the polls to elect Mexico's president, head
of government of the capital, the Chamber of Senators and
Delegates, as well as the Legislative Assembly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
