<DOCNO> XIE20000605.0337 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Demands Britain Return Back Parthenon Sculptures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Greece Monday demanded Britain
return the Parthenon Sculptures, part of the sculptures in the
famous Parthenon, Greece's national symbol, back to Greece.
</P>
<P>
Visiting Greek Foreign Minister George Papandreou told a
committee in the British House of Commons that Greece is
determined to have the sculptures back in Athens, the Greek
capital, by the 2004 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Papandreou said the sculptures were an integral part of the
Parthenon, Greece's national symbol and a cultural artifact of
international importance.
</P>
<P>
The Parthenon Sculptures, also known in Britain as the Elgin
Marbles, were taken to London by British Lord Elgin in the 1830s,
when Greece was under Ottoman Turkish rule.
</P>
<P>
Papandreou said that this masterpiece needed to be reunified on
the Acropolis in Athens, its original location.
</P>
<P>
Calling for a "partnership approach" to the impasse over the
Marbles, Papandreou said his government was willing to consider a
wide range of options, so long as they were back in Athens in time
for the 2004 Olympic Games, which Greece is hosting.
</P>
<P>
The sculptures are currently owned by the British Museum, but
Papandreou said he did not want to get into an argument about the
events of the 1830s, when Lord Elgin acquired them for that
organization while Greece was under Ottoman Turkish rule.
</P>
<P>
Greece maintains that the Marbles were, in effect, stolen,
while Britain says they were purchased legally.
</P>
<P>
However, Papandreou told members of the Select Committee on
Culture, Media and Sport than protecting the integrity of the
monument was far more important than arguing over who owned it.
</P>
<P>
"This masterpiece must be reunified, its integrity if you like
restored, and done so within its original cultural and historical
environment in Athens," he said.
</P>
<P>
Stressing their huge significance to the Greek nation,
Papandreou said he was talking about "the greatest national symbol
of Greece."
</P>
<P>
"It symbolizes the Greek contribution to the cultural heritage
of humankind," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Let us make this a positive thing for the British Museum, a
positive thing for Britain, as well as for Greece," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Greek Government is planning to build a museum to house the
marbles, to be completed in time for the 2004 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
While Papandreou gave evidence to the Select Committee, the
prime minister's official spokesman, Alastair Campbell, gave a
strong signal that Britain was not open to negotiation over the
future of the sculptures.
</P>
<P>
Asked if they would be handed over to Greece, Campbell replied:
"No."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the British Museum itself is keen to keep the
sculptures, arguing that they are best seen as part of a great
international collection visited by six million people each year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000605.0338 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
