<HEADLINE> Brazil Calls for More Agriculture Investments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian Agriculture Minister
Marcus Vicinius Pratini de Moraes Monday called for more
investment in agriculture in order to raise this sector's
competitivity in the market.
</P>
<P>
With the use of barely 127 million hectares of delimited land,
Brazil will be able to triple its current production of grain up
to 250 million tons a year, together with 90 million tons of
fruits and 11 million tons of meat, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
He said the government is granting priority to increases of
exports of agribusiness based on technology, quality and
sanitation, environmental protection, marketing and logistics
investing.
</P>
<P>
Pratini de Moraes said that Brazil's agribusiness exports will
reach this year 23.2 billion U.S. dollars, compared to 1999's
registered 19.9 billion, and in consequence, this sector's trade
balance surplus will go up to 16.5 billion dollars from 13.4
billion dollars last year. 
</P>
