<HEADLINE> Gore Vows to Launch "Second American Revolution" Via Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 5 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Vice President Al Gore
vowed Monday to carry out a "second American Revolution" linking
the people and their government via the Internet if he becomes
president.
</P>
<P>
Gore, in a speech at North Carolina State University, promised
that as president he would have nearly all federal services online
by 2003.
</P>
<P>
"The power of government should not be locked away in
Washington but put at your services, no further away than your
keyboard," the presumptive Democratic presidential candidate said.
</P>
<P>
Under his plan, Gore said, people could use the Internet to get
information about Social Security benefits, to apply for a home
loan, to report a crime or to find the health plan that would work
best for them.
</P>
<P>
"With your help, as president, I will lead a second American
Revolution, to make our self-government far less costly, far more
effective and far more relevant to every American," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also proposed to double the nation's investment in
information technology, which now accounts for about one-third of
the country's economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Gore and Commerce Secretary William M. Daley recently released
a report showing that such spending has grown from 243 billion
dollars in 1995 to 510 billion dollars last year. 
</P>
