<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Soon to Confirm Full Israeli Pullback </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
There remain only a few issues to be resolved, including the
identification of the practical line on the Lebanon border, said
spokesman Fred Eckhard.
</P>
<P>
U.N. experts, including cartographers and legal and military
advisers, are on the ground Monday conducting the task of
identifying the withdrawal line and are currently meeting at the
headquarters of the U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon (UNIFIL) at
Naquora, Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
Israel invaded Lebanon in 1978 and carved up a border strip as
a so-called "security zone" in 1985 to allegedly protect its
northern area from cross-border attacks by Lebanese Muslim
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council adopted resolutions 425 and 426 after
the Israeli invasion, demanding immediate and unconditional
Israeli withdrawal from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The Jewish state decided earlier this year to pull out from
Lebanon by July 7. However, it completed withdrawal of its troops
from south Lebanon on May 24.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon has rejected its military presence in south Lebanon,
claiming that some areas along the borderline are still occupied
by Israel.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon insists that its deployment in the south will be done
only after the U.N. confirmation of full Israeli withdrawal from
Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
