<HEADLINE> Russia Sees Great Threat From Chemical, Biological Weapons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Russia sees a greater emerging threat
from chemical and biological weapons using various delivery
systems rather than nuclear arms, the director of a leading Moscow
think-tank said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The director of Moscow's Center for Political Studies, Vladimir
Orlov, who attended the seminar on Russian strategic issues
organized here Monday afternoon by Limes, a geo-political strategy
magazine, said that Putin believes the main threat comes from
terrorist groups, but also "proliferator states."
</P>
<P>
The threat concerns Russia much more than the United States,
Orlov added, saying that Russia offers a "window of vulnerability"
to chemical or biological attack.
</P>
<P>
Orlov said Russia could decide to make "joint efforts" with the
U.S. on the problem, even if they have yet to reach an agreement
on it.
</P>
<P>
He also repeated that one solution could be Putin's proposal
for a local and limited anti-missile system to take care of
delivery systems that could include missiles.
</P>
<P>
"But the Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty must be maintained
without any change," Orlov quoted Putin as believing.
</P>
<P>
Rybakenkov, a Russian diplomat, made the same point, telling
the seminar that the treaty has to be maintained because
deployment of anti-missile interceptors throughout the U.S. could
"destabilize" the Russian nuclear dissuasion.
</P>
<P>
"We don't want a cure that is worse than the disease," he said,
quoting Putin, also pointing that unlike the U.S., Russia has no
black list of "rogue states."
</P>
<P>
He also said that unlike Yeltsin, Putin is in full control of
Russian foreign policy, which will be "less ambiguous, more
predictable, more comprehensible and more realistic." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000605.0348 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Portugal: Minimizing Possible Negative Effects on Women, Common Responsibility </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 5 (Xinhua) -- It is the common
responsibility of the international community to minimize possible
negative effects and to empower women in their efforts to
participate in the globalization process, Portugal said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on behalf of the European Union at the general debate
of the United Nations General Assembly special session on women,
Maria De Belem Roseira, minister for equality of Portugal, said
the world is now connected more closely than ever through trade,
the information revolution, communication and by the growth of a
set of shared global values.
</P>
<P>
Women have often been most profoundly affected by globalization
and systematic discrimination still prevails at many levels,
Roseira said.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, along with challenges, globalization also opens
new perspectives and opportunities for positive development,
Roseira said.
</P>
<P>
"Equal rights and sharing tasks and responsibilities in all
areas of life, including decision-making, must be our focus in the
twenty-first century," Roseira said.
</P>
<P>
"It is most important to fight against specific forms of
discrimination in employment and economic life. It is also
important that an integrated approach be adopted so that our total
environment may be conducive to gender equality and to the full
enjoyment of human rights for all," the minister added.
</P>
<P>
The special session is a follow-up to the Fourth World
Conference on Women in 1995. The five-day special session, also
called Beijing+5, will focus on examples of good practices,
positive actions, lessons learned, obstacles and key challenges
remaining.
</P>
<P>
It will consider further actions and initiatives for achieving
gender equality in the new millennium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
